Annotations.content:
Annotations is a powerful way of adding features to components, structs and classes.
The primary candidate for this feature are components and was originally made for components, hence why most annotations you’ll find are component-centric.
All annotations can found inside Source\Engine\Annotations.

Some systems provide an annotation within their own folder or module. For example, the tag system provides a tag container annotation and it can be found in Source\Engine\Tags

Usage
For a component to use annotations, simply call REGISTER_ANNOTATIONS.
struct [[Reflect]] MyComponent
{
    float MyFloat = 20;

    CATALYST_COMPONENT(MyComponent)

    REGISTER_ANNOTATIONS
    {
    }
};
You then use ADD_ANNOTATION to provide the item with annotations.
For example, this provides MyComponent with an editor icon and a constructor:
struct [[Reflect]] MyComponent
{
    float MyFloat = 20;

    CATALYST_COMPONENT(MyComponent)

    REGISTER_ANNOTATIONS
    {
        ADD_ANNOTATION(Alchemy::EditorIcon{ &quot;Icons/Test.png&quot; });
        ADD_ANNOTATION(Alchemy::ConstructorAnnotation {
            [](void* Ptr) {
                auto* Comp = static_cast&lt;MyComponent*&gt;(Ptr);
                Comp-&gt;MyFloat = 500.0f;
            }
        });
    }
};
You can then fetch annotations like so;
EditorIcon* Icon = AnnotationRegistry::Get().GetAnnotation&lt;EditorIcon, MyComponent&gt;()
External annotation modification
Annotations can be added or overwritten during runtime externally through something like a plugin. But it is recommended to only do this during the modules initialization.
//TODO Create example
See Also

Components — the primary consumer of annotations

Asset-Manager.content:
Alchemy Asset Manager
The Asset Manager is the engine’s central hub for loading, saving, and managing binary data. It provides a high-performance, version-aware serialization system that ensures data integrity and type safety across all engine modules.

Quick Start: The Basics
At its simplest, the Asset Manager allows you to load and save EntityLibrary objects (which act as containers for your game data) and most other types of assets, such as textures.
Loading an Asset
AssetManager* AM = Engine::Get()-&gt;GetSubsystem&lt;AssetManager&gt;();
EntityLibrary* MyLevel = AM-&gt;LoadAsset(&quot;Content/Maps/Level01.alchemyasset&quot;);
Saving an Asset
AM-&gt;SaveAsset(&quot;Content/Maps/Level01.alchemyasset&quot;, *MyLevel);

Creating Reflectable Assets
To make a custom C++ struct saveable as an asset, simply mark it with the [[Reflect]] attribute. The Alchemy Reflector will automatically generate the necessary binary serialization code.
struct [[Reflect]] MyGameData
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(MyGameData)

    float Difficulty = 1.0f;
    Alchemy::String LevelName;
    Alchemy::Array&lt;int&gt; EnemyIDs;
};
Note: All fields are serialized by default. Use [[Transient]] to skip fields that shouldn’t be saved (like runtime-only timers or pointers).

Technical Architecture: Under the Hood
As you move deeper into the engine, the Asset Manager provides “Industry Grade” features to prevent crashes and data corruption.
1. The Asset Header
Every .alchemyasset file begins with a standardized header:

























FieldPurposeMagicA 4-byte signature (ALCH) to verify the file is a valid Alchemy asset.Engine VersionThe Major.Minor.Patch version of the engine that saved the file.Type HashA unique ID for the data type (e.g., EntityLibrary vs. Texture).Asset VersionA custom version number for that specific asset’s format.
2. Type Safety via Compile-Time Hashing
To prevent you from accidentally loading a Texture file into an Animation struct, the engine uses GetTypeHash&lt;T&gt;().
This is a consteval function that generates a unique 32-bit ID based on the compiler’s function signature. If the TypeHash in the file header doesn’t match the TypeHash of the class you are trying to load, the Asset Manager will stop and log an error before any data is parsed.
3. Versioning &amp; Backward Compatibility
The engine tracks two types of versions:

Engine Version: Global format changes (e.g., changing how Alchemy::String is stored).
Asset Version: Changes to a specific system (e.g., adding a new field to all EntityLibrary assets).

When loading, you can check these versions inside your serialization logic to “fix up” old data:
void Serialize(Archive&amp; Ar, MyData&amp; Data)
{
    Ar &amp; Data.BasicField;

    if (Ar.GetAssetVersion() &gt;= 2) {
        Ar &amp; Data.NewFieldAddedInVersion2;
    }
}
4. The Binary Archive
Unlike JSON or XML, Alchemy uses a custom binary Archive.

Speed: Data is bit-streamed directly from disk to memory.
POD Optimization: The Archive detects “Trivially Copyable” types (like int, float, or structs of primitives) and performs a single memcpy for the entire block rather than iterating field-by-field.
Mode Awareness: The same operator&amp; logic is used for both Saving and Loading, reducing code duplication and human error.


Asynchronous Loading
For production environments where hundreds of assets must be loaded without hitching the game thread, the Asset Manager provides a non-blocking AsyncLoadAsset method.
Usage
AssetManager* AM = Engine::Get()-&gt;GetSubsystem&lt;AssetManager&gt;();

AM-&gt;AsyncLoadAsset(&quot;Content/Characters/Hero.alchemyasset&quot;, [](EntityLibrary* LoadedLib)
   {
    if (LoadedLib) {
        Log(&quot;Hero asset is ready to use!&quot;);
        // Add to world, spawn entities, etc.
    }
});
Key Features of Async Loading:

Job System Integration: Loading tasks (File IO + Deserialization) are dispatched to the JobSubsystem and run on background worker threads.
Request Deduplication: If five different systems request the same asset at the same time, the Asset Manager will only perform one disk read. All five callbacks will be queued and executed once the single load operation completes.
Thread Safety: While the data is loaded in the background, the completion callbacks are automatically dispatched back to the Main Thread, ensuring you can safely modify game state or spawn entities in response to an asset being loaded.


Batch Asynchronous Loading
When loading large sets of assets (e.g., streaming in a new world region), using individual AsyncLoadAsset calls in a loop can hitch the game thread due to job dispatch overhead. To solve this, the Asset Manager provides BatchAsyncLoadAssets.
Usage
AssetManager* AM = Engine::Get()-&gt;GetSubsystem&lt;AssetManager&gt;();
Array&lt;String&gt; LevelPaths = { &quot;Cell_0_0.alchemyasset&quot;, &quot;Cell_0_1.alchemyasset&quot;, ... };

AM-&gt;BatchAsyncLoadAssets(LevelPaths, [](const Array&lt;EntityLibrary*&gt;&amp; LoadedLibs)
{
    Log(&quot;All 50 world cells have been loaded in parallel!&quot;);
    for (EntityLibrary* Lib : LoadedLibs)
    {
        // Process batch
    }
});
Why Use Batching?

Reduced Dispatch Overhead: Instead of hitting the job system 50 times for 50 assets, the batch system uses ParallelForBatch to submit the entire workload in a single “wave.” This keeps the game thread 100% smooth even when requesting hundreds of assets.
The “Wave Strategy”: The system processes assets in small chunks (e.g., 5-10 at a time per worker thread). This staggers the OS-level file opening calls, preventing the “Thundering Herd” effect where too many simultaneous disk requests actually slow down the overall throughput.
Instruction Locality: Because worker threads process multiple assets in a tight loop, the CPU stays in the “Deserialization” instruction path longer, improving cache efficiency.

See Also

Catalyst — EntityLibrary, the data container assets are loaded into
Jobs — the job system used for async and batch asset loading

Catalyst/Components.content:
A component is a pure data structure tied to an entity. In the ECP architecture, components should ideally contain no logic, acting only as state containers for Processors to transform.
Declaration
To define a component, create a standard C++ struct, use the [[Reflect]] attribute, and the CATALYST_COMPONENT macro. This ensures the component is recognized by the reflection system and assigned a unique ID.
struct [[Reflect]] HealthComponent
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(HealthComponent)

    float CurrentHealth = 100.0f;
    float MaxHealth = 100.0f;
};
Usage in Code
Components are managed by the EntityLibrary. You can add, retrieve, or remove them using templated methods.
// Adding a component
Library.AddComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;(Entity, { .CurrentHealth = 50.0f });

// Retrieving a component (returns nullptr if not found)
HealthComponent* Health = Library.GetComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Removing a component
Library.RemoveComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;(Entity);
Component Slots
Component Slots allow a single entity to have multiple instances of the same component type, each identified by a unique slot name. This is essential for scenarios like NPCs with multiple mesh components (body, weapon, armor) that need to remain cache-efficient.
Basic Usage
Use the overloaded AddComponent and GetComponent methods that accept a slot name:
// Adding slotted components
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, bodyMesh, &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, weaponMesh, &quot;Weapon&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, armorMesh, &quot;Armor&quot;);

// Retrieving a specific slot
MeshComponent* Weapon = Library.GetComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Get all slots as an iterable span
ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; AllMeshes = Library.GetComponents&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);
for (const auto&amp; Entry : AllMeshes)
{
    ProcessMesh(Entry.Component, Entry.SlotID);
}

// Count slots
uint32_t SlotCount = Library.GetSlotCount&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Remove a specific slot
Library.RemoveComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);
Query Integration
Use ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt; in entity queries to iterate all slots:
auto Query = Library.RegisterQuery(
    EntityQueryBuilder()
        .All&lt;ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt;&gt;()
        .Build()
);

Library.ForEach(Query, [](ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; Meshes)
{
    for (const auto&amp; Entry : Meshes)
    {
        // Entry.Component — pointer to component
        // Entry.SlotID — unique identifier for this slot
    }
});
How Slots Work Internally
Slots are implemented as virtual TypeInfo entries. Each slot name is hashed into a unique TypeInfo that shares the memory layout of the base type but gets its own ID. From the archetype’s perspective, MeshComponent_Body, MeshComponent_Weapon, and MeshComponent_Armor are three entirely separate component types — each occupying its own column.
Unslotted vs Slotted Archetype Layout
Unslotted — an entity with TransformComponent and HealthComponent:
TypeRegistry
  &quot;TransformComponent&quot;  → ID: 0
  &quot;HealthComponent&quot;     → ID: 1

Archetype  Bitset: 1 1 0 0 0 ...
                   │ │
                   │ └─ HealthComponent (ID 1)
                   └─── TransformComponent (ID 0)

Columns (Structure of Arrays):
  Col[0]  TransformComponent  │ E1 │ E2 │ E3 │ E4 │ ...
  Col[1]  HealthComponent     │ E1 │ E2 │ E3 │ E4 │ ...

Slotted — an entity with TransformComponent and three MeshComponent slots:
TypeRegistry
  &quot;TransformComponent&quot;       → ID: 0
  &quot;MeshComponent&quot;            → ID: 1  ← base type, never set on any archetype
  &quot;MeshComponent_Body&quot;       → ID: 2  ← virtual (same struct, unique ID)
  &quot;MeshComponent_Weapon&quot;     → ID: 3  ← virtual
  &quot;MeshComponent_Armor&quot;      → ID: 4  ← virtual

SlotRegistry
  MeshComponent (ID 1)  →  [ Body (ID 2), Weapon (ID 3), Armor (ID 4) ]

Archetype  Bitset: 1 0 1 1 1 0 ...
                   │   │ │ │
                   │   │ │ └─ MeshComponent_Armor  (ID 4)
                   │   │ └─── MeshComponent_Weapon (ID 3)
                   │   └───── MeshComponent_Body   (ID 2)
                   └───────── TransformComponent   (ID 0)
                   NOTE: MeshComponent base (ID 1) is never set

Columns (Structure of Arrays):
  Col[0]  TransformComponent      │ E1 │ E2 │ E3 │ ...
  Col[1]  MeshComponent_Body      │ E1 │ E2 │ E3 │ ...  ← same sizeof(MeshComponent)
  Col[2]  MeshComponent_Weapon    │ E1 │ E2 │ E3 │ ...  ← same sizeof(MeshComponent)
  Col[3]  MeshComponent_Armor     │ E1 │ E2 │ E3 │ ...  ← same sizeof(MeshComponent)

The virtual TypeInfos are purely an ID trick — each slot column stores raw MeshComponent data. The SlotRegistry is the only thing that knows they all belong to the same base type, which is what ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt; and query matching use to reassemble them.
Slot Names Drive Archetype Identity
Because each unique slot name produces a unique virtual TypeInfo ID, two entities with different slot name sets land in different archetypes, even if the slot count is identical:
// These three entities end up in THREE different archetypes:

Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(warrior, bodyMesh,  &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(warrior, swordMesh, &quot;Weapon&quot;);   // Arch A: [Body | Weapon]

Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(archer,  bodyMesh,  &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(archer,  bowMesh,   &quot;Bow&quot;);      // Arch B: [Body | Bow]

Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(mage,    bodyMesh,  &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(mage,    staffMesh, &quot;Staff&quot;);    // Arch C: [Body | Staff]
This splits entities across three separate archetypes, fragmenting memory and reducing ForEach iteration efficiency. Standardise slot names across entity types to keep related entities in the same archetype:
// ✅ All three share Arch A: [Body | Weapon] — one tight memory chunk
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(warrior, swordMesh,  &quot;Weapon&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(archer,  bowMesh,    &quot;Weapon&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(mage,    staffMesh,  &quot;Weapon&quot;);
Use a consistent vocabulary of slot names (e.g. &quot;Body&quot;, &quot;Weapon&quot;, &quot;Offhand&quot;) or a standardized namespace across all NPC types. Entities that genuinely differ in composition (a quadruped with four leg meshes vs. a biped) belong in separate archetypes anyway — that fragmentation is expected and correct.
Slot Hierarchies
Slots on a single entity can declare parent-child relationships using the slot hierarchy API. This is useful for expressing that a sword mesh belongs under a body mesh, or that a collider follows a specific mesh slot — without requiring any new component types or archetype changes.
Hierarchy data is stored in an invisible internal SlotHierarchyComponent that is automatically added to the entity on first use. You never interact with it directly.
Setting Up a Hierarchy
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, bodyMesh,   &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, swordMesh,  &quot;Sword&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;ColliderComponent&gt;(Entity, swordCollider, &quot;SwordCollider&quot;);

// Declare that &quot;Sword&quot; is a child of &quot;Body&quot;
Library.SetSlotParent(Entity, &quot;Sword&quot;, &quot;Body&quot;);

// Declare that &quot;SwordCollider&quot; is a child of &quot;Sword&quot;
// Cross-type parenting is allowed — types don&#039;t need to match
Library.SetSlotParent(Entity, &quot;SwordCollider&quot;, &quot;Sword&quot;);
Querying the Hierarchy
// Get the parent of &quot;Sword&quot; as a MeshComponent
MeshComponent* Parent = Library.GetParentComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Sword&quot;);

// Pointer overload — resolves the slot name from the pointer automatically
// Slightly more expensive due to the reverse column scan
MeshComponent* SwordPtr = Library.GetComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Sword&quot;);
MeshComponent* ParentViaPtr = Library.GetParentComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, SwordPtr);

// Get all ColliderComponent slots that are children of &quot;Sword&quot;
ComponentSpan&lt;ColliderComponent&gt; Colliders = Library.GetChildrenComponents&lt;ColliderComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Sword&quot;);

// Pointer overload for children
MeshComponent* BodyPtr = Library.GetComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Body&quot;);
ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; BodyChildren = Library.GetChildrenComponents&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, BodyPtr);

// Get all slots of type T that have any parent (regardless of which parent)
ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; AllParented = Library.GetChildrenComponents&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Get all slots of type T that have no parent — the roots
ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; Roots = Library.GetRootComponents&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);
Removing a Relationship
// Remove the parent relationship from &quot;Sword&quot; — &quot;Sword&quot; becomes a root again
Library.ClearSlotParent(Entity, &quot;Sword&quot;);

// Query if a slot has a parent
bool HasParent = Library.HasSlotParent(Entity, &quot;Sword&quot;);
Declaring Hierarchies on Prefabs
Slot hierarchies can be declared directly on an EntityPrefab so that every spawned entity already has the correct parent relationships — with no archetype migration cost at spawn time.
EntityPrefab WarriorPrefab;
WarriorPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(bodyMesh,    &quot;Body&quot;);
WarriorPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(swordMesh,   &quot;Sword&quot;);
WarriorPrefab.Add&lt;ColliderComponent&gt;(swordCol, &quot;SwordCollider&quot;);

// Declare hierarchy on the prefab template
WarriorPrefab.SetSlotParent(&quot;Sword&quot;,         &quot;Body&quot;);
WarriorPrefab.SetSlotParent(&quot;SwordCollider&quot;, &quot;Sword&quot;);

Library.BakePrefab(WarriorPrefab);

// Every spawned entity already has the hierarchy — no migration occurs
EntityHandle Warrior = Library.Instantiate(WarriorPrefab);
The prefab API mirrors the runtime API exactly:





















Prefab methodRuntime equivalentPrefab.SetSlotParent(&quot;Child&quot;, &quot;Parent&quot;)Library.SetSlotParent(Entity, &quot;Child&quot;, &quot;Parent&quot;)Prefab.ClearSlotParent(&quot;Child&quot;)Library.ClearSlotParent(Entity, &quot;Child&quot;)Prefab.HasSlotParent(&quot;Child&quot;)Library.HasSlotParent(Entity, &quot;Child&quot;)
Key Properties

Cross-type parenting is allowed. A ColliderComponent slot can be the child of a MeshComponent slot. The hierarchy stores slot names only — types are only used at the query level for the return value.
The SlotHierarchyComponent is invisible. It is never returned by general-purpose queries. Think of it as metadata attached to the entity, not a game-facing component.
No archetype change at runtime. Setting or clearing a parent relationship only modifies a std::unordered_map inside SlotHierarchyComponent. The entity does not migrate archetypes. When declared on a prefab, SlotHierarchyComponent is included in the baked archetype upfront, so spawn cost is zero.
Slots are unique per entity. Because slot names are unique across all component types on a single entity, no type disambiguation is needed in SetSlotParent or ClearSlotParent.

Entity: &quot;Warrior&quot;

  MeshComponent[&quot;Body&quot;]           ← root (no parent)
  ├── MeshComponent[&quot;Sword&quot;]      ← child of &quot;Body&quot;
  │   └── ColliderComponent[&quot;SwordCollider&quot;]  ← child of &quot;Sword&quot;
  └── MeshComponent[&quot;Shield&quot;]     ← child of &quot;Body&quot;
      └── ColliderComponent[&quot;ShieldCollider&quot;] ← child of &quot;Shield&quot;

Auto-Generated Slot Names
When a [[Slottable]] component is added without an explicit slot name, the engine automatically generates a name like &quot;ComponentType_0&quot;, &quot;ComponentType_1&quot;, etc. This provides a safety net for code that doesn’t explicitly track slot names.
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);      // Creates &quot;MeshComponent_0&quot;
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);     // Creates &quot;MeshComponent_1&quot;

// Can still retrieve them
MeshComponent* First = Library.GetComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // Returns &quot;MeshComponent_0&quot;
Best Practices: Always Use Explicit Slot Names
Do not rely on auto-generated slot names. While they provide a safety net, they make code brittle and hard to understand. Always assign meaningful, explicit names to slots:
// ✅ GOOD: Clear semantic names
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity, &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);
// Recommended to use namespaces for strings used frequently
NPCPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity, MyNamespace::ArmorString);

// ❌ AVOID: Relying on auto-generated names
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // &quot;MeshComponent_0&quot;
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // &quot;MeshComponent_1&quot;
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // &quot;MeshComponent_2&quot;
Why explicit names matter:

Readability: Anyone reading GetComponent(entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;) immediately understands what’s being retrieved
Stability: If you refactor the order of additions, auto-generated indices shift; named slots never do
Debugging: Named slots appear in profilers and logs with semantic meaning
Intent: Your code explicitly states “this is the weapon mesh”, not “this is the second mesh”

Auto-generated names exist only as a fallback for simple prototypes or one-off code. Production code should always use explicit names.
Toggle Components
Components can be disabled and re-enabled at runtime without destroying them. A disabled component’s data is fully preserved in memory — it is simply invisible to queries, so processors that iterate that component type skip the entity entirely with zero per-iteration overhead.
This is the correct tool for world streaming, LOD transitions, and any scenario where entities should temporarily stop participating in simulation without the cost of destruction and reconstruction.
How It Works
Disabling a component performs a single archetype migration. The entity moves from an archetype containing T into one containing an internal __Disabled__T virtual type. Because the query’s cached archetype list never includes that destination archetype, disabled entities are never discovered — there is no per-entity branch or check.
Before DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E):
  Archetype [Transform | MeshComponent]   ← query sees this

After:
  Archetype [Transform | __Disabled__MeshComponent]  ← query does NOT see this

Re-enabling performs the reverse migration and restores the original data exactly.
Basic API
// Disable — entity disappears from MeshComponent queries immediately
Library.DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Enable — entity reappears, all data intact
Library.EnableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Toggle — flips current state
Library.ToggleComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Query state
bool bDisabled = Library.IsComponentDisabled&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Read data while disabled, without re-enabling
MeshComponent* Data = Library.GetDisabledComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);
DisableComponent is a no-op if the entity does not have the component or if it is already disabled.
Slot-Specific Overloads
When a component is slottable and an entity carries multiple slots, the no-argument DisableComponent&lt;T&gt; disables all slots of that type at once. To target a single slot, use the slot name or SlotID overloads:
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, bodyMesh,   &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, weaponMesh, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Disable only the weapon — &quot;Body&quot; remains active and visible in queries
Library.DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Enable it again
Library.EnableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Toggle by name
Library.ToggleComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Query state by name
bool bWeaponDisabled = Library.IsComponentDisabled&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Read disabled slot data
MeshComponent* WeaponData = Library.GetDisabledComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);
When iterating a ComponentSpan and you already have a SlotID, use the ID overload to avoid re-hashing the name:
Library.ForEach(Query, [&amp;](EntityHandle E, ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; Meshes)
{
    for (const auto&amp; Entry : Meshes)
    {
        if (ShouldStreamOut(Entry.Component))
        {
            // Zero hashing cost — SlotID comes directly from the span entry
            Library.DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E, Entry.SlotID);
        }
    }
});
Observer Events
Observers can listen for EnableComponent and DisableComponent events separately from AddElement / RemoveElement:
class OnMeshDisabledObserver : public IObserver
{
public:
    OnMeshDisabledObserver()
    {
        ObservedComponent = TypeRegistry::GetType(MeshComponent::StaticName());
        ObservedOperation = ObserverOperation::DisableComponent;
    }

    void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
    {
        // Context.AffectedEntities contains entities whose MeshComponent was just disabled
    }
};
ObserverOperation::Toggle is a convenience alias for EnableComponent | DisableComponent if you want to react to both:
ObservedOperation = ObserverOperation::Toggle;
Performance
Because disabled entities live in a completely separate archetype, query iteration scales linearly with the number of active entities only. Disabling 50% of entities reduces ForEach time by approximately 50% — there is no scan, skip, or branch for disabled entities.
The migration cost on DisableComponent / EnableComponent is the same as a regular AddComponent / RemoveComponent archetype transition. This is a boundary event, not a per-frame cost.
Constructors
Catalyst supports Constructor Annotations. This allows you to run specific initialization logic whenever a component is added to an entity, which is useful for registering data with external systems or generating unique IDs.
These constructors are executed:

Immediately after AddComponent.
During EntityTransaction::Commit.
During EntityPrefab::Instantiate.

// Registering a constructor
AnnotationRegistry::Get().Bind&lt;MyComponent&gt;()
    .Add&lt;ConstructorAnnotation&gt;([](void* Ptr) {
        auto* Comp = static_cast&lt;MyComponent*&gt;(Ptr);
        Comp-&gt;UniqueID = GNextID++;
    });
Architectural Details (Advanced)
Memory Layout (SoA)
Components are stored in Archetypes using a Structure of Arrays (SoA) format. All components of the same type for a specific archetype are stored contiguously in memory.
Pointer Stability
Catalyst uses Chunked Memory (16KB Pages) for component storage. This ensures Pointer Stability: a pointer returned by GetComponent will remain valid for the lifetime of that component on that entity, even if millions of other entities are spawned or other archetypes reallocate.
Bitset Identification
Each component type is assigned a unique uint32_t ID by the TypeRegistry. An entity’s composition is represented by a ComponentBitset, allowing for O(1) comparisons and extremely fast query matching.
See Also

Entity Query — querying entities by component composition
Entity Prefab — defining component defaults as reusable templates
Annotations — constructor annotations and other component metadata

Catalyst/Entity-Library.content:
Entity Library
An EntityLibrary is the top-level container for an entire ECP world. Every entity, component, archetype, query, processor, observer, and relation lives inside one. There is no global world — you always work through a library instance.
Multiple libraries can coexist simultaneously, each representing an entirely independent ECP world. A running game might have one library for the game world, one for the editor viewport, and another inside the asset manager.
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    EntityLibrary                    │
│                                                     │
│  Entities &amp; Records      Archetypes                 │
│  ┌────────────────┐      ┌──────────────────────┐   │
│  │ Index → Record │      │ [TransformComponent, │   │
│  │   0  → null    │      │  HealthComponent]    │   │
│  │   1  → Arch A  │      │   Row 0: Entity 1    │   │
│  │   2  → Arch B  │      │   Row 1: Entity 3    │   │
│  │   3  → Arch A  │      └──────────────────────┘   │
│  └────────────────┘      ┌──────────────────────┐   │
│                          │  [TransformComponent,│   │
│  Processors              │   VelocityComponent] │   │
│  ┌────────────────┐      │    Row 0: Entity 2   │   │
│  │ MovementProc   │      └──────────────────────┘   │
│  │ RenderProc     │                                 │
│  │ AIProc         │      Registered Queries         │
│  └────────────────┘      ┌──────────────────────┐   │
│                          │  Q0: All&lt;Transform&gt;  │   │
│                          │  Q1: All&lt;Transform,  │   │
│                          │      Velocity&gt;       │   │
│                          └──────────────────────┘   │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Creating a Library
Declare an EntityLibrary anywhere. Libraries are value types with value semantics — they can be owned by subsystems, editor tabs, game modules, or tests.
EntityLibrary Library;

// Optional: assign an owning world (for world-level libraries)
Library.OwningWorld = &amp;MyWorld;
Library Tags
Library tags are used to control which processors attach to which libraries. When a library is registered with the EntityLibrarySubsystem, it automatically receives all processors whose LibraryFilter tag query matches the library’s tags.
// Mark this library as a game world library
Library.LibraryTags.AddTag(Engine_GameWorld);

// Mark as an editor viewport library
ViewportLibrary.LibraryTags.AddTag(Engine_Editor_EditorViewport);
A processor declared with LibraryFilter.RequireTag(Engine_GameWorld) will only attach to libraries tagged with Engine_GameWorld — not to the editor viewport library. This is the primary mechanism for controlling processor scope.
Registering with the Engine
To have the engine tick your library every frame and auto-attach processors, register it with the EntityLibrarySubsystem.
EntityLibrarySubsystem* Subsystem = Engine.GetSubsystem&lt;EntityLibrarySubsystem&gt;();

// Register — all matching processors are instantiated immediately
Subsystem-&gt;Register(&amp;Library);

// Unregister when the library is no longer active
Subsystem-&gt;Unregister(&amp;Library);
Scoped Registration (RAII)
For temporary libraries (editor tabs, test contexts, etc.), use RegisterScoped to guarantee automatic unregistration when the owning scope exits.
{
    ScopedLibraryRegistration Scope = Subsystem-&gt;RegisterScoped(&amp;ViewportLibrary);
    // ViewportLibrary is now ticked every frame

} // ← Unregistered here automatically
Creating Entities
Basic Entity Creation
// Create an entity with no components
EntityHandle Entity = Library.CreateEntity();

// Immediately check if a handle is valid
if(Entity.IsValid())
{
    Library.AddComponent&lt;TransformComponent&gt;(Entity);
}

// Check if an entity is still alive (not destroyed)
bool bAlive = Library.IsEntityAlive(Entity);
Destroying Entities
Library.DestroyEntity(Entity);

// The handle is now stale — IsEntityAlive returns false
// IsEntityAlive uses the generation counter, so stale handles
// are detected even if the entity index has been reused
Entity Handle Internals
EntityHandle (64-bit)
┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Upper 32 bits: Generation │  Lower 32 bits: Index │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Generation: incremented each time an index is recycled
  Index 0:    permanently reserved as ENTITY_NULL

// Validity check — generation mismatch means the slot was reused
bool bAlive = (Library.Generations[Handle.GetIndex()] == Handle.GetGeneration());

The Entity Lifecycle
A typical entity goes through the following stages:
1. CreateEntity()        → Allocate an index, bump generation, no archetype
        │
        ▼
2. AddComponent&lt;T&gt;()     → Place entity into a matching archetype
   AddComponent&lt;T&gt;()     → Migrate to a new archetype (edges are cached)
        │
        ▼
3. IsEntityAlive()       → true (generation matches)
   GetComponent&lt;T&gt;()     → returns pointer into archetype column
   ForEach(...)          → entity is visited by matching queries
        │
        ▼
4. RemoveComponent&lt;T&gt;()  → Migrate to a smaller archetype
        │
        ▼
5. DestroyEntity()       → Entity removed from archetype
                           Index placed in FreeIndices pool
                           Generation incremented (stale handles detected)

Structural Changes
AddComponent and RemoveComponent
Every AddComponent or RemoveComponent moves the entity to a different archetype. These archetype migrations are cheap because the library maintains a cached edge graph: moving from archetype A to “A + T” re-uses a pre-calculated pointer.
// Adding a component (migrates to a larger archetype)
TransformComponent&amp; Transform = Library.AddComponent&lt;TransformComponent&gt;(Entity);
Transform.Position = {0.0f, 0.0f, 0.0f};

// Removing a component (migrates to a smaller archetype)
Library.RemoveComponent&lt;VelocityComponent&gt;(Entity);
Entity Transaction (Batched Changes)
If you need to add or remove several components at once, use an EntityTransaction. It batches all changes into a single archetype migration rather than one per add/remove, which is significantly cheaper for large sets of changes.
// Without a transaction — three migrations:
Library.AddComponent&lt;RenderComponent&gt;(Entity);
Library.AddComponent&lt;ShadowComponent&gt;(Entity);
Library.RemoveComponent&lt;PlaceholderTag&gt;(Entity);

// With a transaction — one migration:
auto Transaction = Library.Modify(Entity);
Transaction.Add&lt;RenderComponent&gt;();
Transaction.Add&lt;ShadowComponent&gt;();
Transaction.Remove&lt;PlaceholderTag&gt;();
Transaction.Commit(); // ← single archetype migration happens here
// Note: components are NOT visible on the entity until Commit()
The transaction is especially valuable during world loading or prefab post-processing when an entity receives many components in sequence.
Deferred Changes (EntityCommandBuffer)
Direct structural changes (AddComponent, DestroyEntity, etc.) are not safe to call inside a ForEach callback — modifying archetypes while iterating over them is undefined behavior. The EntityCommandBuffer lets you record commands during iteration and apply them afterward.
EntityCommandBuffer Buffer;

Library.ForEach(DyingQuery, [&amp;Buffer](HealthComponent&amp; Health, EntityHandle Entity)
{
    if(Health.CurrentHealth &lt;= 0.0f)
    {
        // Safe — this records the command, doesn&#039;t execute it yet
        Buffer.DestroyEntity(Entity);
        Buffer.AddComponent&lt;DeadMarker&gt;(Entity);
    }
});

// Apply all recorded commands now that iteration is complete
Buffer.Playback(Library); // also calls Clear() automatically
Supported Commands
Buffer.AddComponent&lt;T&gt;(Entity, Data);
Buffer.RemoveComponent&lt;T&gt;(Entity);
Buffer.AddMarker&lt;T&gt;(Entity);
Buffer.RemoveMarker&lt;T&gt;(Entity);
Buffer.DestroyEntity(Entity);
Buffer.Instantiate(&amp;BakedPrefab);  // prefab must outlive Playback()
Buffer.Enqueue([](EntityLibrary&amp; Lib) { /* arbitrary logic */ });
The buffer uses a page-based allocator (16 KB pages) and is designed to be zero-allocation for typical usage within a single frame.
Processors and Command Buffers
Inside a processor’s Execute method, a command buffer is available via ProcessorContext. Always use it for structural changes rather than modifying the library directly:
void MyProcessor::Execute(ProcessorContext&amp; Context)
{
    Context.Library.ForEach(MyQuery, [&amp;Context](HealthComponent&amp; Health, EntityHandle Entity)
    {
        if(Health.CurrentHealth &lt;= 0.0f)
        {
            Context.CommandBuffer.DestroyEntity(Entity);
        }
    });
    // The library flushes Context.CommandBuffer automatically after all processor Execute&#039;s return
}
Ticking and Lifecycle
Manual Tick
When you own a library outside the subsystem, call Update yourself:
Library.Update(DeltaTime);
Update runs all processors registered on the library and flushes all pending observer events.

Note: Do not call Update inside Crucible tests. Tests should call processor or query methods directly.

Clearing a Library
Clear() resets the entire library - all entities, archetypes, queries, and processor state are destroyed.
Library.Clear();
Multiple Concurrent Libraries
The real power of the library model is that several independent ECP worlds can run simultaneously. Each has its own entities, archetypes, and processors, and they never interfere with each other.
                        ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
                        │        EntityLibrarySubsystem       │
                        │                                     │
                        │  ┌────────────┐  ┌────────────────┐ │
                        │  │  GameWorld │  │ EditorViewport │ │
                        │  │  Library   │  │   Library      │ │
                        │  │            │  │                │ │
                        │  │ Processor  │  │ Processor      │ │
                        │  │ (Game tag) │  │ (Editor tag)   │ │
                        │  └────────────┘  └────────────────┘ │
                        │                                     │
                        │  ┌─────────────────────────────┐    │
                        │  │   AssetManager Library      │    │
                        │  │   (Asset Manager tag)       │    │
                        │  └─────────────────────────────┘    │
                        └─────────────────────────────────────┘
Each library is only ticked and modified by processors whose LibraryFilter matches its tags. An editor viewport library and a game world library can coexist with zero crosstalk.
Merging Libraries
Merge bulk-copies all entities and components from one library into another. The source library is left unmodified.
// Copy everything from ChunkLibrary into the main world
MainLibrary.Merge(ChunkLibrary);

// Preserve original EntityHandles from the source (default)
MainLibrary.Merge(ChunkLibrary, /*bPreserveIDs=*/ true);

// Assign new handles to avoid ID collisions across independently-loaded worlds
MainLibrary.Merge(ChunkLibrary, /*bPreserveIDs=*/ false);
The merge is archetype-aware — for each archetype in the source, it calls GetOrCreateArchetype in the target, bulk-allocates rows, then copies all component columns via CopyConstructor (or memcpy as a fallback).
Merging is useful for:

Streaming open world chunks into a single runtime library
Consolidating distributed ECS registries
Copying test fixture state between test runs

Serialization
EntityLibrarySerializer provides binary save and load for an entire library.
#include &quot;Catalyst/Serialization/EntityLibrarySerializer.h&quot;

// Save
EntityLibrarySerializer::Serialize(Library, &quot;SavedWorld.bin&quot;);

// Load
EntityLibrarySerializer::Deserialize(Library, &quot;SavedWorld.bin&quot;);
The binary format uses the ALCH magic number and a version field. On load:

Archetypes are recreated via GetOrCreateArchetype.
Entity rows are bulk-allocated.
Component data is reconstructed via each type’s registered serializer.


Note: Components without a registered serializer are skipped during load with a warning. Ensure all persistent component types have serialization support via the reflection system’s operator&amp;(Archive&amp;).

Processor Management
Processors can be added to a library either automatically (via EntityLibrarySubsystem and LibraryFilter) or manually.
// Manual attachment — for specialized or test processors
Library.AddProcessor(new MyProcessor());

// Inline processor — lambda-based, no class needed
Library.AddProcessor(
    InlineProcessorBuilder(&quot;MovementProcessor&quot;)
        .OnExecute([](ProcessorContext&amp; Ctx) {
            Ctx.Library.ForEach(MoveQuery, [](TransformComponent&amp; T, VelocityComponent&amp; V) {
                T.Position += V.Velocity * Ctx.DeltaTime;
            });
        })
        .Build()
);

// Remove a specific processor
Library.RemoveProcessor(ProcessorPtr);
For production code, prefer class-based processors registered via AutoRegisterProcessor&lt;T&gt; so they attach automatically to all matching libraries.
Common Patterns
Game World Setup
// In a world subsystem or game module:
EntityLibrary GameLibrary;
GameLibrary.OwningWorld = &amp;World;
GameLibrary.LibraryTags.AddTag(Engine_GameWorld);

ScopedLibraryRegistration Scope = Subsystem-&gt;RegisterScoped(&amp;GameLibrary);
// All processors tagged Engine_GameWorld are now active
Editor Viewport
EntityLibrary ViewportLibrary;
ViewportLibrary.LibraryTags.AddTag(Engine_Editor_EditorViewport);

// Create the camera entity directly — no prefab needed for one-offs
EntityHandle Camera = ViewportLibrary.CreateEntity();
ViewportLibrary.AddComponent&lt;TransformComponent&gt;(Camera);
ViewportLibrary.AddComponent&lt;CameraComponent&gt;(Camera);

ScopedLibraryRegistration Scope = Subsystem-&gt;RegisterScoped(&amp;ViewportLibrary);
// Tab close → Scope destructor unregisters automatically
Standalone Library (No Subsystem)
Useful for asset processing, tools, or simulation previews that should not participate in the main game tick:
EntityLibrary AssetLibrary;
// No tags — no processors auto-attach
// No registration — not ticked by the subsystem

// Manually tick if needed
AssetLibrary.Update(DeltaTime);
// Or query directly without ticking
AssetLibrary.ForEach(Query, [](MyComponent&amp; C) { ... });
Crucible Tests
#if ALCHEMY_WITH_CRUCIBLE
BEGIN_SPEC(LibrarySpec, &quot;Catalyst.EntityLibrary&quot;)
END_SPEC(LibrarySpec)

void LibrarySpec::Define()
{
    Describe(&quot;Entity lifecycle&quot;, [this]()
    {
        It(&quot;should invalidate a handle after destruction&quot;, [this]()
        {
            EntityLibrary Library;
            EntityHandle Entity = Library.CreateEntity();
            Library.AddComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;(Entity);

            TestTrue(&quot;alive before destroy&quot;, Library.IsEntityAlive(Entity));
            Library.DestroyEntity(Entity);
            TestFalse(&quot;dead after destroy&quot;, Library.IsEntityAlive(Entity));
        });
    });
}
#endif
See Also

Components — adding, removing, and querying components and slots
Entity Prefab — high-performance entity spawning via baked blueprints
Entity Query — ForEach, ForEachParallel, and filtered iteration
Processor — processors that run against a library every tick
Relations — typed directional links between entities within a library
Tags and Markers — lightweight per-entity flags

Catalyst/Entity-Prefab.content:
Entity Prefab
An EntityPrefab is a high-performance blueprint for creating entities. It allows you to define a composition of components and their default values once, then spawn thousands of identical entities with virtually zero overhead.
Creating a Prefab
Prefabs act as mutable containers during configuration. You can add components and immediately modify their data.
EntityPrefab OrcPrefab;

// Add components and tweak values
auto&amp; Stats = OrcPrefab.Add&lt;StatsComponent&gt;();
Stats.Health = 500;
Stats.Strength = 20;

OrcPrefab.Add&lt;AIComponent&gt;({ .Behavior = EAIBehavior::Aggressive });
OrcPrefab.Add&lt;TransformComponent&gt;();
Adding Component Slots
Prefabs support the same slotted component API as the EntityLibrary. Use the two-parameter overload to add multiple instances:
EntityPrefab NPCPrefab;

// Add unslotted base component
NPCPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(defaultMesh);

// Add slotted components with names
NPCPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(bodyMesh, &quot;Body&quot;);
NPCPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(weaponMesh, &quot;Weapon&quot;);
NPCPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(armorMesh, &quot;Armor&quot;);

// Retrieve and modify slots before baking
MeshComponent* Weapon = NPCPrefab.Get&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(&quot;Weapon&quot;);
if (Weapon) {
    Weapon-&gt;Visibility = true;
}
The slot data is preserved and applied to every entity instantiated from the prefab, just like regular components.
Best Practices: Always Use Explicit Slot Names
When working with slotted components in prefabs, always assign meaningful, explicit names to your slots. Do not rely on auto-generated slot names. While the engine supports auto-generation as a safety net (e.g., &quot;MeshComponent_0&quot;, &quot;MeshComponent_1&quot;), it should only be used in simple prototypes or one-off code.
// ✅ GOOD: Clear semantic names
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity, &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);
// Recommended to use namespaces for strings used frequently
NPCPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity, MyNamespace::ArmorString);

// ❌ AVOID: Relying on auto-generated names
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // &quot;MeshComponent_0&quot;
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // &quot;MeshComponent_1&quot;
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // &quot;MeshComponent_2&quot;
Why explicit names matter:

Readability: Anyone reading Get&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(&quot;Weapon&quot;) immediately understands what’s being retrieved
Stability: If you refactor the order of additions, auto-generated indices shift; named slots never do
Debugging: Named slots appear in profilers and logs with semantic meaning
Intent: Your code explicitly states “this is the weapon mesh”, not “this is the second mesh”

Auto-generated names exist only as a fallback for simple prototypes or one-off code. Production prefabs should always use explicit names.
The Baking Process
Before a prefab can be spawned, it must be Baked. Baking is a one-time optimization step where the EntityLibrary pre-calculates the target archetype and organizes the component data into the engine’s internal memory layout.
// This resolves the Archetype and caches memory offsets once.
Library.BakePrefab(OrcPrefab);
Instantiation (Spawning)
Once baked, you can instantiate entities from the prefab. This is the fastest way to create entities in Catalyst.
Single Spawn
Creates a single entity and returns its handle.
EntityHandle NewOrc = Library.Instantiate(OrcPrefab);
Bulk Spawn
The most optimized path for spawning many entities at once (e.g., world loading or unit waves).
// Spawns 1,000 entities in a single pass
Library.Instantiate(OrcPrefab, 1000);
Constructors
Prefabs fully support Constructor Annotations. When an entity is instantiated from a prefab:

The prefab’s tweaked data is copied into the entity.
The component’s Alchemical Constructor is executed.

This allows you to define “static” defaults in the prefab while still allowing every spawned entity to have unique logic (like a UniqueID or a SpawnTimestamp) generated at the moment of birth.
Performance Details (Advanced)
O(1) Spawning
Unlike the standard CreateEntity + AddComponent flow, Instantiate is an O(1) operation.

No Bitset Hashing: The target archetype is already known.
No Map Lookups: Column indices and Constructor pointers are pre-cached during the Bake step.
Raw Memcpy: Data is moved from the prefab to the archetype using highly optimized bulk memory copies.

Bulk Optimization
When using the bulk Instantiate overload, the engine performs a single memory allocation for the entire batch. This eliminates the “Resizing Wall” and ensures that spawning 100,000 entities is nearly as fast as spawning one, amortized across the batch.
See Also

Components — component slots and slot hierarchies, which prefabs support
Annotations — constructor annotations that run on prefab instantiation

Catalyst/Entity-Query.content:
Entity Query
The Entity Query system is the primary mechanism for retrieving entities and their components from an EntityLibrary. It is designed for maximum performance through Archetype Caching, ensuring that the cost of fetching data is proportional to the number of matching archetypes, not the total number of entities.
Defining a Query
Queries are constructed using the EntityQueryBuilder. This provides a human-readable fluent API to describe the requirements of your logic.
// 1. Describe the requirements
EntityQueryDescription Desc = EntityQueryBuilder()
    .All&lt;PositionComponent&gt;()
    .All&lt;VelocityComponent&gt;()
    .None&lt;StaticTag&gt;()
    .Build();

// 2. Register with the library to get a persistent ID
EntityQueryID MoveQuery = Library.RegisterQuery(Desc);
Matching Rules

All: The entity must have every component in this list.
Any: The entity must have at least one component from this list.
None: The entity must not have any components from this list.

Executing a Query
The most efficient way to process entities is using the ForEach and ForEachParallel methods.
Sequential Iteration (ForEach)
Used for standard logic that runs on a single thread. It resolves component pointers once per memory chunk to eliminate lookup overhead.
Library.ForEach(MoveQuery, [](PositionComponent&amp; Pos, const VelocityComponent&amp; Vel)
{
    Pos.Value += Vel.Value * DeltaTime;
});
Parallel Iteration (ForEachParallel)
Used for high-volume data processing. It automatically distributes entities across all available CPU cores using the engine’s Job System.
// Automatically uses the active JobBuilder context
Library.ForEachParallel(MoveQuery, [](PositionComponent&amp; Pos, const VelocityComponent&amp; Vel)
{
    // Logic runs in parallel across worker threads
    Pos.Value += Vel.Value * DeltaTime;
});
Span Queries (Multi-Instance Components)
When querying entities with slotted components (multiple instances of the same component type), use ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt; in the query builder. This iterates all slots of that type on matching entities.
// Query for all entities with MeshComponent slots
EntityQueryID MeshQuery = Library.RegisterQuery(
    EntityQueryBuilder()
        .All&lt;ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt;&gt;()
        .Build()
);

// Iterate all entities and their mesh slots
Library.ForEach(MeshQuery, [](ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; Meshes)
{
    for (const auto&amp; Entry : Meshes)
    {
        // Entry.Component — pointer to the mesh
        // Entry.SlotID — identifier for this slot
        RenderMesh(Entry.Component);
    }
});
Mixed Span and Regular Components
You can combine span and regular components in the same query:
EntityQueryID Query = Library.RegisterQuery(
    EntityQueryBuilder()
        .All&lt;TransformComponent&gt;()          // Regular: single instance
        .All&lt;ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt;&gt;() // Span: multiple instances
        .Build()
);

Library.ForEach(Query, [](TransformComponent&amp; Transform, ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; Meshes)
{
    for (const auto&amp; Entry : Meshes)
    {
        RenderMeshAt(Entry.Component, Transform.Position);
    }
});
Span Query Semantics

All&lt;ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt;&gt;: Entity must have at least one slot of type T.
Any&lt;ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt;&gt;: Optional — entity may have slots of type T.
None&lt;ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt;&gt;: Entity must have zero slots of type T.

Span queries iterate only entities that have slots. Entities with only the unslotted base component do not match.
Filtered Query
The filtered query system provides two methods for processing a specific subset of entities rather than the entire world. The subset is an Array&lt;EntityHandle&gt; — typically the result of a relation lookup such as GetChildrenEntities.
Serial (FilteredForEach)
Array&lt;EntityHandle&gt; Children = Library.GetChildrenEntities&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Parent);

EntityQueryID Query = Library.RegisterQuery(
    EntityQueryBuilder().All&lt;HealthComponent&gt;().Build());

Library.FilteredForEach(Children, Query, [](HealthComponent&amp; Health)
{
    Health.CurrentHealth -= DamageThisFrame;
});
Parallel (FilteredForEachParallel)
Distributes the subset across worker threads. Returns a JobBuilder* so you can chain a Then() dependency after all batches complete. Returns nullptr if called outside a processor context (falls back to serial automatically).
// Must be called from inside a processor&#039;s Execute method (requires active JobBuilder)
if(JobBuilder* Builder = Context.Library.FilteredForEachParallel(Children, Query,
    [](HealthComponent&amp; Health)
    {
        Health.CurrentHealth -= DamageThisFrame;
    }))
{
    // Optional: chain work that runs after all parallel batches finish
    Builder-&gt;Then(&quot;PostDamage&quot;, [this]() { NotifyDamageComplete(); });
}
The EntitiesPerJob parameter controls batch granularity (default: 64). From job system benchmarks, batches below ~50 entities cause thread-communication overhead to dominate — keep this value at 50 or above.
The query still acts as a filter in both methods — entities in the array that do not match it are skipped silently.
When to Use Filtered Queries
Filtered queries are the right choice when your logic only applies to a relation-defined subset of the world — a turret’s targets, a squad’s members, a room’s occupants.
Because filtered queries resolve each entity individually via a per-entity Records[] lookup, they have a higher per-entity cost than ForEach. Use the crossover formula to decide:
FilteredForEach wins when:  subset_size  &lt;  world_size × (ForEach ns/entity / FilteredForEach ns/entity)

Measured benchmarks on this engine (Ryzen 9950x, 50k entity world):

























Methodns/entityNotesForEach~4 nsContiguous archetype sweep, no per-entity indirectionFilteredForEach~169 nsPer-entity Records[] lookup, column ptrs cached per chunkFilteredForEachParallel~179 nsSimilar to serial at small sizes; parallel overhead dominates below ~500 entities
This gives a crossover of roughly 3.3% of the world size. In a 50k world that is ~1,650 entities — if your subset is smaller than that, FilteredForEach wins over a full sweep.
FilteredForEachParallel matches serial performance at small subset sizes. It becomes worthwhile when per-entity work is heavy enough that parallel execution time exceeds the job dispatch overhead (~15 µs per thread handoff).
Caching the Subset
GetChildrenEntities is O(N) in the number of children. Calling it every frame on a large fan-out is expensive. Cache the result and re-query only when the hierarchy changes:
// Stored on the processor or relevant component
Array&lt;EntityHandle&gt; CachedChildren;
bool bHierarchyDirty = true;

// In the processor tick:
if(bHierarchyDirty)
{
    CachedChildren = Library.GetChildrenEntities&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(RootNode);
    bHierarchyDirty = false;
}

Library.FilteredForEach(CachedChildren, DamageQuery, [](HealthComponent&amp; Health) { ... });
How it Works (Advanced)
Archetype Caching
When a query is registered, the library scans all existing archetypes and caches those that match. When a new archetype is created at runtime, it is automatically checked against all active queries. This ensures that ForEach only touches relevant memory.
Bitset Matching
Catalyst uses a 512-bit ComponentBitset to represent archetype signatures. Query matching is performed using extremely fast bitwise AND/OR operations, allowing the engine to filter thousands of archetypes in microseconds.
Chunked Memory Awareness
The iteration helpers are aware of Catalyst’s 16KB Page architecture. They iterate chunk-by-chunk to maintain cache locality and handle page boundaries efficiently, especially during parallel execution.
See Also

Processor — processors register and execute queries
Relations — relation queries produce the filtered entity lists used with FilteredForEach
Jobs — ForEachParallel dispatches work through the job system

Catalyst/Processor/Observer.content:
Observer
Observers are specialized Processors that react to specific ECS events rather than running every frame. They are ideal for event-driven logic such as initializing physics when a component is added or playing a sound when an entity is destroyed.
Creating an Observer
To create an observer, inherit from IObserver. You must specify the component and the operation you are watching in the constructor.
class PhysicsInitializer : public IObserver
{
public:
    PhysicsInitializer()
    {
        // 1. What component are we watching?
        ObservedComponent = TypeRegistry::GetType(RigidBody::StaticName());

        // 2. What event triggers us?
        ObservedOperation = ObserverOperation::AddElement;
    }

    virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
    {
        // Logic goes here
    }

    virtual const char* GetName() const override { return &quot;PhysicsInit&quot;; }
};
Event Types
Observers use the ObserverOperation enum to define triggers. You can use individual flags or convenient helper groups:

































FlagDescriptionAddElementA component was added to an existing entity.RemoveElementA component was removed from an entity.CreateEntityAn entity was born with this component (e.g. via Prefab).DestroyEntityAn entity with this component was destroyed.DisableComponentA component was disabled on an entity (entity migrated out of active queries).EnableComponentA disabled component was re-enabled on an entity.
Helper Groups

Add: Combines AddElement | CreateEntity. Use this to catch “birth” and “attachment” in one go.
Remove: Combines RemoveElement | DestroyEntity. Use this for all cleanup scenarios.
Toggle: Combines EnableComponent | DisableComponent. Use this to react to any visibility change.
All: Combines every possible operation.

Observing Toggle Events
Toggle Components fire DisableComponent and EnableComponent events that are distinct from structural add/remove. This lets systems react to streaming, LOD, or gameplay enable/disable cycles without confusing them with entity creation or destruction.
class [[Reflect]] StreamingObserver : public IObserver
{
public:
    StreamingObserver()
    {
        ObservedComponent = TypeRegistry::GetType(MeshComponent::StaticName());

        // React to disable only — e.g. stop GPU uploads when mesh goes invisible
        ObservedOperation = ObserverOperation::DisableComponent;

        // Or react to both:
        // ObservedOperation = ObserverOperation::Toggle;
    }

    virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
    {
        for (EntityHandle Entity : *Context.AffectedEntities)
        {
            // Component data is still accessible via GetDisabledComponent while disabled
            MeshComponent* Mesh = Context.Library.GetDisabledComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);
            if (Mesh) ReleaseGPUResources(Mesh-&gt;MeshID);
        }
    }
};
DisableComponent and EnableComponent events are not fired by AddComponent or RemoveComponent — they are strictly for toggle transitions. An observer watching DisableComponent will never fire when an entity is destroyed.
Processing Changes
Observers operate on a Change List. The ProcessorContext provides access to the specific entities that triggered the event.
virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
{
    // Method A: Iterate the specific entities that changed (Random Access)
    for (EntityHandle Entity : *Context.AffectedEntities)
    {
        RigidBody* Body = Context.Library.GetComponent&lt;RigidBody&gt;(Entity);
        Body-&gt;Initialize();
    }
}
Handling Large Change Lists
A common pitfall with observers is the cost of Random Memory Access. Accessing components for a scattered list of entities is slower than a sequential query.
If an observer is triggered by a massive batch (e.g., spawning 10,000 entities), you can run a query inside the observer instead of iterating the change list. This allows the engine to use SoA (Structure of Arrays) optimizations while still only running the logic when an event occurs.
virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
{
    // Method B: Run a Query for cache efficiency (Sequential Access)
    // Useful if you expect many entities to trigger this at once.
    Context.Library.ForEach(MyOptimizedQuery, [](RigidBody&amp; Body) {
        Body.Initialize();
    });
}
Best Practices
Automatic Batching
The engine automatically batches events. If multiple entities trigger an event in one frame, your observer will run once with the combined list.
Parallel Dispatch
Observers are integrated into the engine graph and run on worker threads by default. They can run in parallel with other systems, ensuring that event-driven logic doesn’t stall the game thread.
See Also

Processor — Observers inherit from IObserver, a specialization of the processor concept
Entity Query — observers can run queries internally for cache efficiency on large change lists

Catalyst/Processor/Processor.content:
Processors are the logic units of the Alchemy ECS. While the Entity Library holds the data, Processors define how that data transforms over time. They are managed by the EntityLibrarySubsystem and executed automatically every frame.
Creating a Processor
To create logic, inherit from IProcessor and implement Execute. The most common pattern is to iterate over entities using a EntityQuery.
class MovementProcessor : public IProcessor
{
public:
    EntityQueryID Query;

    virtual void Initialize(EntityLibrary&amp; Lib) override
    {
        // Define what data we need once during startup
        Query = Lib.RegisterQuery(EntityQueryBuilder()
            .All&lt;PositionComponent&gt;()
            .All&lt;VelocityComponent&gt;()
            .Build());
    }

    virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
    {
        // Optimized parallel iteration
        Context.Library.ForEachParallel(Query, [](PositionComponent&amp; Pos, const VelocityComponent&amp; Vel)
        {
            Pos.Value += Vel.Value * Context.DeltaTime;
        });
    }

    virtual const char* GetName() const override { return &quot;MovementProcessor&quot;; }
};
Configuration &amp; Ordering
Processors often depend on each other (e.g., Physics must run before Rendering). You configure this in the constructor using Tags.
MovementProcessor()
{
    // Define ordering relative to other systems
    ExecuteAfter.push_back(Tags::Input);
    ExecuteBefore.push_back(Tags::Physics);

    // Grouping for mass-activation/deactivation
    ExecutionGroup = Tags::GameLogic;
}
Thread Affinity
By default, Processors run on background worker threads (JobAffinity::Any). If you need to access main-thread-only APIs (like Windowing or OpenGL), you must specify it.
virtual JobAffinity GetAffinity() const override 
{ 
    return JobAffinity::Main; 
}
Inline Processors
For cases where a full subclass is unnecessary — editor tooling, debug hooks, test fixtures, or short-lived runtime logic — use InlineProcessorBuilder to create a processor directly from lambdas.
struct MyState { EntityQueryID Query; };
auto State = std::make_shared&lt;MyState&gt;();

Library.AddProcessor(
    InlineProcessorBuilder(&quot;HealthDrain&quot;)
        .OnInitialize([State](EntityLibrary&amp; Lib, IProcessor* Proc) {
            State-&gt;Query = Lib.RegisterQuery(EntityQueryBuilder().All&lt;HealthComponent&gt;().Build());
            Proc-&gt;ExecuteAfter.push_back(Tags::Input);
            Proc-&gt;LibraryFilter = TagQuery::MatchTag(Tags::GameWorld);
        })
        .OnExecute([State](const ProcessorContext&amp; Ctx, IProcessor* Proc) {
            Ctx.Library.ForEach(State-&gt;Query, [&amp;](HealthComponent&amp; HP) {
                HP.Value -= 1.0f * Ctx.DeltaTime;
            });
        })
);
Both callbacks receive an IProcessor* pointing to the processor itself. All configuration — ExecuteBefore, ExecuteAfter, ExecutionGroup, LibraryFilter — is set directly on that pointer inside OnInitialize. This means the builder never has to mirror IProcessor’s fields; any new fields added to IProcessor are automatically available with no changes to the builder.
State Between Callbacks
OnInitialize and OnExecute are separate lambdas, so they cannot share local variables directly. The standard pattern is a shared_ptr to a plain struct captured by both:
struct State { EntityQueryID Query; };
auto State = std::make_shared&lt;State&gt;();

// Both lambdas capture State by value (copies the shared_ptr, not the data)
.OnInitialize([State](EntityLibrary&amp; Lib, IProcessor* Proc) { State-&gt;Query = ...; })
.OnExecute([State](const ProcessorContext&amp; Ctx, IProcessor* Proc) { /* use State-&gt;Query */ })

Important: Never capture stack variables by reference in either callback. Both lambdas outlive the call site — the builder is consumed immediately, but the processor continues running for the library’s lifetime.

Thread Affinity Without OnInitialize
If you need main-thread execution but have no initialization work, use WithAffinity on the builder — it is the one setting that must be known before Initialize runs:
Library.AddProcessor(
    InlineProcessorBuilder(&quot;UISync&quot;)
        .WithAffinity(JobAffinity::Main)
        .OnExecute([](const ProcessorContext&amp; Ctx, IProcessor* Proc) {
            // Safe to call ImGui / windowing APIs here
        })
);
When to Use a Named Processor Instead
Inline processors are a convenience, not a replacement. Prefer a named subclass when:

The processor will be reused across multiple libraries or modules
It carries significant state (many query IDs, configuration fields, caches)
It needs to be auto-registered via [[Reflect]] so it applies to all matching libraries automatically

Advanced Usage
The Active JobBuilder
During the execution of a Processor, Catalyst maintains a thread_local pointer to the active JobBuilder. This allows helper functions like ForEachParallel to automatically attach their sub-tasks to the current frame’s execution graph without explicit parameter passing.
Manual Job Dispatch
Sometimes you need raw control over the Job System. You can access the JobBuilder directly from the ProcessorContext to dispatch custom tasks.
virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
{
    // Dispatch a custom job that depends on the processor&#039;s completion
    Context.Builder.Dispatch(&quot;ComplexTask&quot;, []() { ... });
}
Entity Command Buffers (ECB)
Processors are physically prohibited from making immediate structural changes (adding/removing components or destroying entities) to the EntityLibrary while executing. This ensures:

Thread Safety: Multiple processors can run in parallel without race conditions on memory layout.
Iterator Stability: Adding an entity won’t cause a query iteration to skip or repeat entities due to archetype transitions.

Instead, all structural changes are recorded into the EntityCommandBuffer provided by the ProcessorContext.
Core Commands
The ECB supports all standard ECS operations. These are recorded in O(1) time and played back at the end of the frame.
virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
{
    Context.Library.ForEachParallel(Query, [&amp;](EntityHandle E, const HealthComponent&amp; Health)
    {
        if (Health.Value &lt;= 0)
        {
            // Record destruction - occurs after all processors finish
            Context.Commands.DestroyEntity(E);
        }
        else if (Health.Value &lt; 50)
        {
            // Record component addition
            Context.Commands.AddComponent&lt;ShieldComponent&gt;(E, { .Strength = 10 });
        }
    });
}
Toggle Commands
Toggle Components must also go through the ECB inside processors, since enabling or disabling a component is a structural change (archetype migration).
// Disable all slots of MeshComponent on this entity
Context.Commands.DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E);

// Disable a specific slot by name
Context.Commands.DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Re-enable
Context.Commands.EnableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E);
Context.Commands.EnableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Toggle (direction resolved at Playback time, not at record time)
Context.Commands.ToggleComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E);
The toggle direction for ToggleComponent is resolved when the command buffer plays back, not when you record it. This means the flip always reflects the entity’s actual state at the end of the frame rather than at the moment the processor ran.
Deferring Custom Logic
Beyond structural changes, you can defer arbitrary code execution using Defer. This is useful for logic that must run on the main thread or must happen after the world state has stabilized.
Context.Commands.Defer([=](EntityLibrary&amp; Lib) {
    // This lambda runs during playback on the main thread
    Log(&quot;Entity %d has been processed!&quot;, E.GetIndex());
});
Note on Captures: When using Defer, always capture by value ([=]). Capturing by reference is unsafe as the processor’s stack frame will be gone by the time the command buffer plays back.
Implementation Details

Linear Allocation: The ECB uses a page-based linear allocator (16KB pages). Recording a command is essentially a pointer increment, making it extremely fast.
Determinism: Commands are played back in the exact order they were recorded. If System A records a change before System B, that order is preserved during playback. - We have made the decision to sacrifice performance over determinism when it comes to the ECB. There are ways of batching commands or sorting them for better cache efficiency, or maybe even using the job system to multithread these commands, but in nearly every case when you’re working with the command buffer, you want it to be deterministic and on the game thread.
Playback Window: The EntityLibrarySubsystem automatically flushes the command buffer once all processors have reached a synchronization point (usually the end of the Update tick).

See Also

Entity Query — queries are defined and executed within processors
Observer — event-driven variant of a processor
Jobs — the job system processors dispatch parallel work to
Source/Engine/Catalyst/InlineProcessor.h - full InlineProcessorBuilder API

Catalyst/Relations.content:
Relations
A Relation is a typed, directional link between two entities. It is implemented as a third relation entity that holds the two endpoint handles and a type marker — neither primary entity is modified.
Owner Entity ──[OwnsRelation]──► Target Entity
                    │
              Relation Entity
              ├─ RelationOwner { Owner }
              ├─ RelationTarget { Target }
              └─ OwnsRelation (marker)

This design keeps the primary entities structurally unchanged. The relation entity can also carry additional user-defined components, making it a first-class citizen in the ECS.
Terminology — “owner” and “target” are the generic terms. In a hierarchy context, the owner is the child and the target is the parent (e.g. AddRelation&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Child, Parent)).

Defining a Relation Type
Derive from CatalystRelation and annotate with CATALYST_RELATION(). The configuration fields are set in the constructor and cached on the first AddRelation call for that type — construction cost is paid exactly once per type, not per call.
struct OwnsRelation : Alchemy::CatalystRelation
{
    CATALYST_RELATION(OwnsRelation)

    OwnsRelation()
    {
        UniqueParent      = true;  // Owner may only own one target at a time
        OnParentDestroyed = Alchemy::ERelationCleanupPolicy::DestroyRelated;
        OnChildDestroyed  = Alchemy::ERelationCleanupPolicy::DestroyRelation;
    }
};
Configuration Fields









































FieldTypeDefaultDescriptionUniqueParentboolfalseEach owner may hold at most one relation of this type. Adding a second replaces the first.UniqueChildboolfalseEach target may be targeted by at most one relation of this type. Adding a second replaces the first.MaxDepthint0If &gt; 0, prevents adding a relation that would exceed this depth in the graph. 0 = unlimited.OnParentDestroyedERelationCleanupPolicyDestroyRelationWhat happens when the owner entity is destroyed.OnChildDestroyedERelationCleanupPolicyDestroyRelationWhat happens when the target entity is destroyed.
Cleanup Policies





















PolicyEffectDestroyRelationDestroys the relation entity only. Both primary entities survive.DestroyRelatedDestroys the relation entity and the other endpoint entity.DoNothingLeaves the relation entity alive with a dangling handle. The caller is responsible for cleanup.

Built-in Relations
ChildOfRelation
The standard parent/child hierarchy relation. Each entity may have at most one parent (UniqueParent = true). Destroying either endpoint destroys the relation entity; neither primary entity is destroyed.
EntityHandle Parent = Library.CreateEntity();
EntityHandle Child  = Library.CreateEntity();

Library.AddRelation&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Child, Parent);

Working with Relations
Adding a Relation
EntityHandle RelationEntity = Library.AddRelation&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Child, Parent);
Returns the relation entity handle. This can be used to attach additional data to the relation itself (see Attaching Data to Relations).
If UniqueParent = true and the owner already has a relation of this type, the existing relation is silently destroyed before the new one is created.
Removing a Relation
Library.RemoveRelation&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Child, Parent);
Destroys the relation entity and removes it from both internal indexes. Both primary entities remain alive.
Checking for a Relation
bool bHasParent = Library.HasRelation&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Child, Parent);
Getting the Relation Entity Directly
EntityHandle RelEnt = Library.GetRelationEntity&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Child, Parent);
Useful for reading or writing components attached to the relation entity itself.

Querying Relations
All relation lookups are O(1) index operations.
Get All Children
Returns all owner entities that have a relation of this type pointing to the given target.
Array&lt;EntityHandle&gt; Children = Library.GetChildrenEntities&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Parent);
Get the Parent (Unique Relations)
For relation types with UniqueParent = true, each owner has at most one parent. Use GetParentEntity for a direct single-entity result.
EntityHandle Parent = Library.GetParentEntity&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Child);
Asserts that UniqueParent = true on the relation type.
Get All Parents (Non-Unique Relations)
For relation types without UniqueParent, an owner may have multiple relations of the same type.
Array&lt;EntityHandle&gt; Parents = Library.GetParentEntities&lt;MyMultiRelation&gt;(Child);

Attaching Data to Relations
Because a relation is a real entity, you can add components to it just like any other entity. This allows storing metadata — such as edge weights in a graph, timestamps, or damage values in a combat relation — directly on the relation.
struct DamageRelation : Alchemy::CatalystRelation
{
    CATALYST_RELATION(DamageRelation)
};

struct DamageAmount
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(DamageAmount)
    float Value = 0.0f;
};

EntityHandle Rel = Library.AddRelation&lt;DamageRelation&gt;(Attacker, Defender);
Library.AddComponent&lt;DamageAmount&gt;(Rel, { .Value = 50.0f });

Processing Relation Subsets
When you need to run logic only on entities that are connected to a particular node, use FilteredForEach with the result of a relation query. See Entity Query — Filtered Query for full details and the performance crossover point.
Array&lt;EntityHandle&gt; Children = Library.GetChildrenEntities&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Parent);
EntityQueryID Query = Library.RegisterQuery(EntityQueryBuilder().All&lt;HealthComponent&gt;().Build());

Library.FilteredForEach(Children, Query, [](HealthComponent&amp; Health)
{
    Health.CurrentHealth -= DamageThisFrame;
});

Cleanup on Destruction
When Library.DestroyEntity(Entity) is called, the relation system runs before the entity is marked dead. This ensures index lookups remain valid during cleanup.
Owner destroyed: All relations where Entity is the owner are processed using OnParentDestroyed.
Target destroyed: All relations where Entity is the target are processed using OnChildDestroyed.
Cleanup is recursive for DestroyRelated — if destroying a target also triggers a cascade, that cascade runs to completion before moving on.

Architectural Details (Advanced)
Why a Relation Entity?
Catalyst’s ComponentBitset is fixed at 512 bits, keyed by sequentially assigned type IDs. The alternative (Flecs-style pair encoding) would require one unique type ID per (RelationType, TargetEntity) combination. A scene hierarchy with 1,000 parent nodes would exhaust 1,000 IDs just for parent relations, overflowing the bitset. The relation entity pattern has no such constraint.
Index Structure
EntityLibrary maintains two internal FlatMap indexes:

RelationsByOwner — maps (owner_index, relation_type_id) → array of relation entity handles
RelationsByTarget — maps (target_index, relation_type_id) → array of relation entity handles

Keys are packed as (entity_index &lt;&lt; 32 | type_id) into a uint64_t. Both indexes are updated atomically on every AddRelation, RemoveRelation, and DestroyEntity call.
Relation Config Caching
CatalystRelation-derived types are default-constructed exactly once (on the first AddRelation&lt;T&gt; call) to read their config. The result is stored in KnownRelationTypes and reused for all subsequent calls and during DestroyEntity cleanup.
See Also

Entity Query — FilteredForEach is used to process relation subsets
Components — relation entities can carry components like any other entity

Catalyst/Tags-and-Markers.content:
Alchemy’s ECS uses the word “tag” for its hierarchical tagging system, so what other ECS frameworks call “tags” (empty components used as flags) are called Markers here. This page covers both concepts and when to use each.
Markers
A marker is a data-less flag attached to an entity. It is defined using the CATALYST_MARKER macro:
struct IsSelected   { CATALYST_MARKER(IsSelected)   };
struct IsSleeping   { CATALYST_MARKER(IsSleeping)   };
struct PendingDeath { CATALYST_MARKER(PendingDeath) };
How Markers Are Stored
Markers are not stored in archetypes. Instead, each entity has a dedicated ComponentBitset (a 512-bit bitset) in EntityLibrary::MarkerRecords. Adding or removing a marker is a single bitset set/reset operation — O(1) with no memory allocation and no archetype remapping.
This means the engine supports up to 512 unique marker and component types across all modules.



                  NOTE



The component bitset might either be increased to 1024, or reworked in favour for less performance, but in exchange for no limit across all modules.


Adding and Removing Markers
// Direct library calls
Library.AddMarker&lt;IsSelected&gt;(Entity);
Library.RemoveMarker&lt;IsSelected&gt;(Entity);
bool bSelected = Library.HasMarker&lt;IsSelected&gt;(Entity);

// Via EntityCommandBuffer (deferred)
CommandBuffer.AddMarker&lt;IsSelected&gt;(Entity);
CommandBuffer.RemoveMarker&lt;IsSelected&gt;(Entity);
Unlike components, adding or removing a marker never triggers an archetype move. This makes markers ideal for state that changes frequently at runtime.
Querying by Marker
Marker filtering is expressed in EntityQueryBuilder using WithMarker and WithoutMarker:
EntityQueryBuilder()
    .All&lt;TransformComponent, HealthComponent&gt;()
    .WithMarker&lt;IsSelected&gt;()        // Entity MUST have this marker
    .WithoutMarker&lt;PendingDeath&gt;()   // Entity must NOT have this marker
    .Build();
Marker filtering happens per-entity during iteration, not at archetype selection time. The query system first narrows candidates by archetype (using component bitsets), then applies a bitwise AND against RequiresMarkers and ExcludesMarkers for each entity in the matching chunks:
// Conceptual execution inside ForEach
const ComponentBitset&amp; M = MarkerRecords[Entity.GetIndex()];
if((M &amp; Desc.RequiresMarkers) != Desc.RequiresMarkers) continue;
if((M &amp; Desc.ExcludesMarkers).any()) continue;
Because this is two bitset operations per entity, marker queries are fast even at scale.
Internal Use: Relations
The Relation system also uses markers internally to identify the type of a relation entity. Each relation entity receives a marker matching its relation type at creation, allowing the library to identify and clean up the relation during entity destruction.

Tags
The engine provides a TagComponent, which contains a TagCounterContainer (a reference-counted tag set). This is attached to entities that need complex hierarchical classification.
// Tags are attached via the engine Tags system — see [[Tags]]
Library.AddComponent&lt;TagComponent&gt;(Entity);
Library.GetComponent&lt;TagComponent&gt;(Entity)-&gt;Container.AddTag(Weapon_Melee_Sword);
TagComponent is typically added at entity construction and rarely removed. Adding or removing a tag within the component does not cause an archetype change — the TagComponent itself is the component; its contents are internal state.
Querying with Tags
Tags are not queryable via EntityQueryBuilder directly. Instead, build a TagQuery and evaluate it against a TagComponent:
TagQuery Query = TagQuery::Builder()
    .MatchAnyTags({ Weapon_Melee, Weapon_Ranged })
    .Build();

// Inside a processor or ForEach lambda:
if(Query.Matches(TagComp-&gt;Container)) { ... }
Because tag queries are evaluated per-entity (rather than per-archetype), they are slower than component or marker queries for bulk iteration. The trade-off is significantly more expressive power: hierarchical matching, logical combinators (AND, OR, NOT), and child-tag traversal.

Choosing Between Markers and Tags

































ScenarioUseBinary on/off state that changes at runtimeMarkerFiltering entities in bulk queriesMarkerClassifying entity types (tree, vehicle, NPC)TagHierarchical “is a child of” queriesTagComplex multi-condition logic (AND/OR/NOT)TagFrequently toggled per-frame flagsMarker
In general: reach for a marker first. Only use a tag when you need hierarchy or logical composition that markers can’t express.

See Also

Tags — the Tags system that this section references
Tag Query — building complex boolean queries over tag containers
Entity Query — archetype-based queries for component filtering

Crucible/Crucible.content:
Crucible
Crucible is a framework designed to test and validate the functionality of Alchemy Engine.
Creating tests
Crucible uses a “Behavior-Driven Development” (BDD) style for its tests. These types of tests are often called “spec testing”.
To implement a specification test, it’s fairly simple:
#if ALCHEMY_WITH_CRUCIBLE

BEGIN_SPEC(MySpec, &quot;Game.MyFeature&quot;)
    float Health;
    EntityHandle TestEntity;
END_SPEC(MySpec)

void MySpec::Define()
{
    Describe(&quot;Entity Management&quot;, [this]()
    {
        // Setup: Runs before every test below
        BeforeEach([this]()
        {
            Health = 100.0f;
            TestEntity = World-&gt;CreateEntity();
        });

        // Cleanup: Runs after every test below
        AfterEach([this]()
        {
            if (Health == 100)
            {
               LogError(&quot;Health is still 100.
                         Damage or healing did not apply&quot;);
            }
        });

        It(&quot;should take damage&quot;, [this]()
        {
            ApplyDamage(TestEntity, 10.0f);
            TestTrue(&quot;Health reduced&quot;, Health == 90.0f);
        });

        It(&quot;should heal&quot;, [this]()
        {
            // Health is reset to 100.0f here automatically!
            ApplyHeal(TestEntity, 10.0f);
            TestTrue(&quot;Health capped&quot;, Health == 100.0f);
        });
    });
}

#endif
Note the #if ALCHEMY_WITH_CRUCIBLE at the start and #endif at the end. These preprocessor macros will make sure that your tests never make it to release builds and makes sure this code never tries to compile whenever Crucible is not present.
The overall goal is to create very human-readable code by describing the logic that’s about to happen, then stating it does/should/could/would (whatever the context of the test is). You then have numerous test functions to evaluate if a result is as you expected.
For more examples, you can review the Engine/Source/Crucible/Tests folder, as it contains all tests for the engine. These tests can also be used to learn how to use certain frameworks by viewing them as “code samples”.
Running tests with breakpoints
Breakpoints won’t work on tests triggered by the frontend, since it’s running the raw .exe file.
To have breakpoints work, you must select AlchemyRunner in your IDE configuration and edit it. In Rider, you’ll see Program arguments and from there you can pass in the same arguments that the frontend is automating for you.
To run a test through these arguments, you can pass in -RunTest=”My.Test”. This can also take an array of tests, like so: -RunTest=”Test.One, Test.Two”. Now when you run AlchemyRunner, your breakpoints will trigger.
Recommendations

All tests should be found under a “Tests” folder. For the engine, this is mandatory. But for plugins and for your personal projects, there’s nothing stopping you from putting tests anywhere you want
Tests should try to be as fast as possible, instantaneous if possible. This is important for environments where you might have a lot of tests, or an environment where all tests are automatically triggered at some point (like once a week, once a day, per commit, etc).

See Also

Testing Guide — full guide for writing, running, and analyzing tests (especially for AI agents)
Profiler — Tracy integration for benchmark tests

Extension-Points.content:
Extension Points
Extension Points are points where you can insert custom code to be processed at a later time in the same callstack of the owner of the Extension Point’s processing logic.
The primary use case is ImGui. For example; if you want to add a button to the tools dropdown, you can get the tools extension point and directly add a button, all without referencing the tool section or even understanding where it is in the codebase.
Example
//Create an extension point
static ExtensionHandle ToolsHandle = ExtensionSubsystem::RegisterExtension(&quot;Tools&quot;);
//Placed inside your code, but executed by the tools menu.
ExtensionSubsystem::Push(TestHandle, []()
{
    ImGui::TextColored(ImVec4(0, 1, 0, 1), &quot;Extension Point Working!&quot;);
    ImGui::Button(&quot;Extension Button&quot;);
});
//The code found inside the tools menu
if (ImGui::Begin(&quot;Tools menu&quot;))
{
    ImGui::Text(&quot;Tools:&quot;);
    ImGui::Separator();
    /**Run the pushed lambda.
     * The pushed lambda may have been on a worker thread,
     * but we are now on the game thread. This is fine,
     * and is desired. This just means the pushed logic
     * will be executed on the game thread. */
    ExtensionSubsystem::Dispatch(TestHandle);
    ImGui::Separator();
}
ImGui::End();
The handle is optional. It’s also possible to use the name of the extension point.
Notes

This system might get replaced with Resonance as it shares very similar concepts

See Also

Resonance — the messaging system that overlaps conceptually with extension points
Sigil — the UI framework extension points primarily target

Input/Input-Processors.content:
Input Processors
An IInputProcessor is a step in the input pipeline that can read and optionally consume events before they reach the next processor. This is how editor tools intercept mouse drag, how ImGui claims keyboard focus, and how custom gameplay systems can suppress input in cutscenes.
Processor Chain
Processors are sorted by Priority (highest first), with RunAfter&lt;T&gt; / RunBefore&lt;T&gt; for explicit ordering relative to specific types.
Priority 200+  →  Custom editor processors (e.g. viewport camera drag)
Priority 100   →  UIInputProcessor         (consumes events ImGui claims)
Priority   0   →  InputRouterProcessor     (routes remaining to entities)

After each processor runs, consumed events are stripped before the next processor sees them. A processor at priority 100 can prevent priority 0 from ever seeing a keyboard event.
Built-in Processors
UIInputProcessor
Runs at priority 100. Reads ImGui::GetIO().WantCaptureKeyboard and WantCaptureMouse each frame. When ImGui owns focus, keyboard events (DeviceID 0) and mouse button/scroll events (DeviceID 1) are consumed before they reach the router. Mouse move events are never consumed — the viewport still needs cursor position.
InputRouterProcessor
Runs at priority 0. For every active EntityLibrary, queries all entities that have InputReceiverComponent + InputStateComponent + InputProfileComponent and resolves enabled profile slots into InputStateComponent.
Writing a Custom Processor
class CutsceneInputBlocker : public IInputProcessor
{
public:
    CutsceneInputBlocker()
    {
        Priority = 50; // Between UI (100) and router (0)
    }

    virtual void ProcessInput(Array&lt;InputEvent&gt;&amp; Events,
                              const InputProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
    {
        if(!bCutsceneActive) return;

        // Consume all keyboard and mouse events during cutscene
        for(InputEvent&amp; Ev : Events)
        {
            if(Ev.DeviceID == 0 || Ev.DeviceID == 1)
                Ev.Consume();
        }
    }

    virtual const char* GetName() const override { return &quot;CutsceneInputBlocker&quot;; }

    bool bCutsceneActive = false;
};
Register it with InputSubsystem:
auto* Blocker = new CutsceneInputBlocker();
Engine::Get()-&gt;GetSubsystem&lt;InputSubsystem&gt;()-&gt;RegisterProcessor(Blocker);
Ordering with RunAfter / RunBefore
When priority numbers feel arbitrary, use explicit ordering constraints instead:
class MyToolProcessor : public IInputProcessor
{
public:
    MyToolProcessor()
    {
        Priority = 150;
        RunBefore&lt;UIInputProcessor&gt;();  // Must run before ImGui consumes events
    }
};
The subsystem performs a topological sort respecting both Priority and RunAfter/RunBefore constraints. Circular dependencies are detected and logged.
InputProcessorContext
Every processor receives a const InputProcessorContext&amp; with:

























FieldTypePurposeDeltaTimefloatFrame delta in secondsLibrariesconst Array&lt;EntityLibrary*&gt;&amp;All active entity librariesInputconst IInputStateProvider&amp;Raw key state queries (IsKeyDown, GetMouseDelta, etc.)
Event Types



































