Instanced-Struct.content:
Instanced Struct
InstancedStruct is a type-erased container that can hold any struct registered with the Reflection system by value. It acts as a safe, polymorphic wrapper for data, similar to std::any but with reflection awareness and deep-copy semantics.
It is a foundational building block for systems that need to pass arbitrary data around, such as the Resonance messaging system.
Key Features

Type Erasure: Can hold any reflected struct.
Value Semantics: Handles deep copying and moving of the contained data using the TypeRegistry’s lifecycle functions.
Memory Management: Automatically manages the memory buffer for the contained struct.
Type Safety: Provides safe Get&lt;T&gt;() methods that check the stored type against the requested type.

Usage Guide
1. Registering a Struct
Any struct intended to be used with InstancedStruct must reflected.
struct [[Reflect]] MyData
{
    int ID;
    float Value;
};
2. Creating an InstancedStruct
You can create an InstancedStruct from any instance of a reflected type.
// Create from value (Copy)
MyData Data { 42, 3.14f };
InstancedStruct Wrapper = InstancedStruct::Make(Data);

// Create from r-value (Move)
InstancedStruct Wrapper2 = InstancedStruct::Make(MyData{ 100, 1.0f });
3. Accessing Data
To retrieve the data, you must know the type you expect. The accessor returns a pointer, or nullptr if the type mismatch.
// Const Access
const MyData* Ptr = Wrapper.Get&lt;MyData&gt;();
if(Ptr)
{
    Log(&quot;ID: {}&quot;, Ptr-&gt;ID);
}

// Mutable Access
MyData* MutablePtr = Wrapper.GetMutable&lt;MyData&gt;();
if(MutablePtr)
{
    MutablePtr-&gt;Value += 1.0f;
}
4. Lifecycle Management
InstancedStruct automatically calls the correct Destructor, Copy Constructor, and Move Constructor for the contained type.
{
    InstancedStruct Wrapper = InstancedStruct::Make(MyComplexType{});
    // MyComplexType is stored in Wrapper&#039;s internal buffer.
} 
// Wrapper goes out of scope -&gt; MyComplexType Destructor is called automatically.
API Reference

































MethodDescriptionMake(Value)Static helper to create an InstancedStruct from a value.Get&lt;T&gt;()Returns const T* to the data if types match, otherwise nullptr.GetMutable&lt;T&gt;()Returns T* to the data if types match, otherwise nullptr.IsValid()Returns true if the struct holds valid data.Reset()Destroys the contained data and frees memory.GetTypeInfo()Returns the TypeInfo* of the contained data.
See Also

Resonance — the primary consumer of InstancedStruct for message payloads

Jobs.content:
Job System
The Alchemy Job System is a high-performance threading engine designed to scale your game across every available CPU core. It allows the engine to perform thousands of small tasks simultaneously without the developer having to manage raw threads.

1. The Simple Version (Start Here)
What is a Job?
Think of a Job as a small “to-do” item. Instead of the main thread doing everything alone, it breaks the work into jobs and hands them to a group of “Worker Threads” who do the work in the background.
How to use it
To run code in the background, you use a JobBuilder.
// 1. Get the Job System
auto* Jobs = Engine::Get()-&gt;GetSubsystem&lt;JobSubsystem&gt;();

// 2. Create a Builder to add tasks
JobBuilder Builder(*Jobs);

// 3. Dispatch a simple task
Builder.Dispatch(&quot;MySimpleTask&quot;, []() {
    Log(&quot;I am running in the background!&quot;);
});

2. The Power User Version (Chaining &amp; Groups)
Real games often need things to happen in a specific order. For example: “Calculate Physics, and THEN Update Animations.”
Chaining with .Then()
You can use the .Then() function to create a “Fence”. All jobs added before the .Then() must finish before the job inside the .Then() begins.
JobBuilder Builder(*Jobs);

// These two run in parallel (at the same time)
Builder.Dispatch(&quot;TaskA&quot;, []() { /* ... */ });
Builder.Dispatch(&quot;TaskB&quot;, []() { /* ... */ });

// This runs ONLY after TaskA and TaskB are both finished
Builder.Then(&quot;TaskC&quot;, []() {
    Log(&quot;A and B are done, now I can run!&quot;);
});
Processing Large Lists (ParallelFor)
If you have 10,000 entities, you don’t want to run 10,000 separate Dispatch calls. Instead, use ParallelFor to split the list into chunks automatically.
// Splits 1000 items into chunks and processes them across all CPU cores
Builder.ParallelFor(&quot;ProcessEntities&quot;, 1000, [](uint32_t index) {
    // Process item at &#039;index&#039;
});

3. The “God Mode” Version (Hierarchies &amp; Recursion)
The system is hierarchical. A job can spawn its own “Child Jobs”. The “Parent Job” is not considered finished until all of its children (and grandchildren) are 100% complete.
Builder.Dispatch(&quot;Grandparent&quot;, []() {
    auto Jobs = Engine::Get()-&gt;GetSubsystem&lt;JobSubsystem&gt;();
    JobBuilder ChildBuilder(*Jobs);

    // Spawn children
    ChildBuilder.ParallelFor(&quot;ChildTask&quot;, 100, [](int i) {
        // This is a grandchild!
    });

    // The &#039;Grandparent&#039; job effectively &#039;waits&#039; for all 100 children 
    // without actually blocking the thread.
});

4. For the nerds (Technical Deep Dive)
Our job system is HEAVILY inspired by CDPR’s amazing GDC talk. I highly recommend reading it.
Counter-Based Dependencies
Alchemy uses Atomic Counters instead of traditional Task Graphs.

Every job is assigned a WaitCounter and an AccumulateCounter.
A job stays in a “Waiting List” as long as its WaitCounter &gt; 0.
When a job finishes, it decrements its AccumulateCounter.
If a counter hits zero, the system automatically moves all jobs waiting on that counter into the “Ready Queue”.

Work-Stealing
The system uses a Multi-Level Work-Stealing Queue architecture:

LIFO Local Queue: Each worker has a private queue. It pushes/pops from the front (Last-In, First-Out) to keep data hot in the CPU cache.
FIFO Stealing: When a worker runs out of work, it looks at other workers’ queues and “steals” from the back (First-In, First-Out). This moves the “oldest” (and usually largest) tasks to other cores to balance the load.
Main Thread Help: When the main thread calls WaitForCounter(), it doesn’t sleep. It becomes a temporary worker, stealing jobs from the global pool until the work is done.

Thread Affinity
Some jobs (like Rendering or Window Input) require specific thread context.

Affinity::Any: Default. Can be stolen by any worker.
Affinity::Main: Hard-locked to the thread that initialized the engine.
Affinity::Worker: Locked to the background pool, preventing the main thread from stealing it.

Performance advice

Dispatching jobs has virtually 0 overhead and costs almost nothing to perform (range for starting and ending is usually between 1-7 micro seconds). But sending a task to another thread and managing the job graph and orchestrating the threads is slow (About 15 micro seconds). Whenever possible, you should use ParallelFor(), which can batch your jobs ChunkSize parameter). By batching your jobs, you can dramatically improve cache efficiency. - For example, on a Ryzen 9950x; - 100k jobs being dispatched in a normal for loop on average takes about 48ms - Due to how long it takes for a thread to receive a job, you usually don’t fully saturate the CPU. You’re essentially limited to just the speed of your threads communicating between each other and the time it takes to send jobs and how fast they can alert the job system that it’s finished and ready for a job new.
Batching 100k jobs takes about 1.6ms’s - Do note that you should not have ChunkSize too small. Otherwise, it becomes slower. Setting ChunkSize to 1 will actually cause this to skyrocket to 96ms’s. Typically there are diminishing returns beyond 50
Batching is the best way to fully saturate the CPU. Because you’re batching jobs together, it means the CPU has to do far less jumping back and forth between threads. A thread is given a list of jobs to perform and they can just go down the list with virtually 0 time between jobs.
If you have many different jobs, but still want to batch them, you can call BatchDispatch() (This is actually what ParallelFor() is doing).

See Also

Catalyst — Catalyst’s ForEachParallel is built on top of the job system
Profiler — Tracy integration for measuring job performance

Plugins.content:
Plugins
Plugins are independently-compiled DLLs that extend the engine or editor without modifying engine source. They are discovered automatically at startup and support hot reload during development.

Directory Structure
Plugins live in a Plugins/ directory either at the engine root (bundled plugins) or inside a project directory (project-specific plugins).
Plugins/
└── MyPlugin/
    ├── MyPlugin.alchemyplugin       ← manifest (required)
    ├── Binaries/
    │   └── MyPlugin.dll             ← compiled output (generated by build)
    └── Modules/
        └── MyPlugin/
            ├── MyPlugin.build.cs    ← build rules
            ├── MyPlugin.cpp
            └── MyPlugin.h

The Binaries/ folder is the output directory. The build system writes the DLL there automatically — do not put source files in it.

Manifest (.alchemyplugin)
Each plugin requires a JSON manifest in its root directory, named after the plugin folder.
{
    &quot;Name&quot;: &quot;MyPlugin&quot;,
    &quot;Version&quot;: &quot;1.0.0&quot;,
    &quot;EnabledByDefault&quot;: true,
    &quot;HotReloadable&quot;: true,
    &quot;Description&quot;: &quot;What this plugin does.&quot;,
    &quot;Modules&quot;: [
        { &quot;Name&quot;: &quot;MyPlugin&quot;, &quot;Type&quot;: &quot;Runtime&quot; }
    ]
}
Fields















































FieldTypeDefaultDescriptionNamestringrequiredPlugin identifier. Must match the folder name.VersionstringrequiredSemantic version string.EnabledByDefaultbooltrueWhether the plugin loads automatically. Projects can override this.HotReloadablebooltrueWhether the plugin supports hot reload. Set false for plugins that are unsafe to reload (e.g., plugins that modify global native state).Descriptionstring&quot;&quot;Human-readable description.ModulesarrayrequiredList of DLL modules this plugin contains.
Module Entry
{ &quot;Name&quot;: &quot;MyPlugin&quot;, &quot;Type&quot;: &quot;Runtime&quot; }




















FieldValuesDescriptionNamestringMust match the .build.cs filename and the Binaries/Name.dll output.TypeRuntime, Editor, RuntimeAndEditorControls when the module is loaded. Editor modules are skipped in non-editor builds.

Implementing a Plugin
Every plugin module exports a single factory function and implements the IPlugin interface.
IPlugin Interface
class IPlugin
{
public:
    virtual ~IPlugin() = default;

    virtual void OnLoad(PluginContext* Context) = 0;    // Called once when plugin is loaded
    virtual void OnUpdate(float DeltaTime) = 0;         // Called every frame
    virtual void OnUnload() = 0;                        // Called before plugin is unloaded

    // Optional: called before hot reload replaces this instance.
    // Use this to save any state you want to transfer to the new instance.
    virtual void OnHotReload(PluginContext* Context) {}
};
PluginContext
PluginContext is passed to OnLoad and OnHotReload. It provides access to engine singletons from inside the DLL boundary.
struct PluginContext
{
    void* ImGuiContext = nullptr;           // Cast to ImGuiContext* and pass to ImGui::SetCurrentContext
    void* TypeRegistryInstance = nullptr;   // Cast to TypeRegistry* if needed
    void* AnnotationRegistryInstance = nullptr;
    void* EngineInstance = nullptr;         // Cast to Engine* if needed
    const char* PluginDir = nullptr;        // Absolute path to the plugin root folder
};
Singletons are passed as void* because DLL boundaries do not share static state. You must set ImGui::SetCurrentContext in OnLoad if your plugin renders any ImGui.
Factory Function
Each module must export a CreatePlugin function:
extern &quot;C&quot; __declspec(dllexport) IPlugin* CreatePlugin()
{
    return new MyPluginImpl();
}
This is the only required export. The plugin manager calls it after loading the DLL.

Minimal Example
Plugins/MyPlugin/Modules/MyPlugin/MyPlugin.cpp
#include &quot;Engine/Plugins/IPlugin.h&quot;
#include &quot;Engine/Logging/Log.h&quot;
#include &lt;imgui_internal.h&gt;

using namespace Alchemy;

class MyPluginImpl : public IPlugin
{
public:
    void OnLoad(PluginContext* Context) override
    {
        ImGui::SetCurrentContext((ImGuiContext*)Context-&gt;ImGuiContext);
        Log(&quot;Loaded!&quot;);
    }

    void OnUpdate(float DeltaTime) override
    {
        ImGui::Begin(&quot;My Plugin&quot;);
        ImGui::Text(&quot;Hello from MyPlugin&quot;);
        ImGui::End();
    }

    void OnUnload() override
    {
        Log(&quot;Unloaded!&quot;);
    }
};

extern &quot;C&quot; __declspec(dllexport) IPlugin* CreatePlugin()
{
    return new MyPluginImpl();
}
Plugins/MyPlugin/Modules/MyPlugin/MyPlugin.build.cs
public class MyPluginRules : ModuleRules
{
    public MyPluginRules(BuildContext ctx) : base(ctx)
    {
    }
}
An empty build.cs is valid. The build system automatically links engine headers and the core DLL for plugin modules.
Plugins/MyPlugin/MyPlugin.alchemyplugin
{
    &quot;Name&quot;: &quot;MyPlugin&quot;,
    &quot;Version&quot;: &quot;1.0.0&quot;,
    &quot;EnabledByDefault&quot;: true,
    &quot;Modules&quot;: [
        { &quot;Name&quot;: &quot;MyPlugin&quot;, &quot;Type&quot;: &quot;Runtime&quot; }
    ]
}

Hot Reload
Plugins are hot-reloadable by default. When the engine detects that a plugin’s DLL has changed on disk, it automatically reloads it without restarting.
How It Works
Every frame, PluginManager::Tick() checks the last-write timestamp of each hot-reloadable plugin DLL against what it recorded at load time. If the timestamp has advanced:

The new DLL is shadow-copied to a temp file and loaded
If the copy fails (linker is still writing), reload is silently deferred to the next frame
Once loaded: OnHotReload() is called on the old instance, then OnUnload()
The old DLL is freed, the new instance takes over

This means you can rebuild the plugin DLL while the engine is running and changes appear automatically.
Shadow Copy
The engine never loads the DLL from Binaries/ directly. It copies it to a temp file first (%TEMP%/MyPlugin_HotReload_N.dll). This frees the original file for overwriting by the linker while the old copy keeps running.
Preserving State Across Reloads
Implement OnHotReload() to save any state before the instance is destroyed:
void OnHotReload(PluginContext* Context) override
{
    // Save any state you need before this instance is destroyed.
    // The new instance will start fresh with OnLoad().
    Log(&quot;[MyPlugin] About to be reloaded, saving state...&quot;);
}
Note: since the old and new instances are in different DLLs, you cannot transfer C++ objects directly. Serialize to a neutral format (e.g., write to a file or a global engine registry) if you need state continuity.
Opting Out
Set &quot;HotReloadable&quot;: false in the manifest to disable hot reload for a specific plugin. The plugin will only reload on engine restart.
{
    &quot;Name&quot;: &quot;CoreSystemPlugin&quot;,
    &quot;HotReloadable&quot;: false,
    ...
}
Use this for plugins that register global native hooks, modify memory allocators, or are otherwise unsafe to unload mid-session.
Project Overrides
A project can enable or disable specific plugins regardless of EnabledByDefault in the manifest. See the project descriptor documentation for the PluginOverrides field.

Discovery Paths
The plugin manager scans two directories on startup:

{EngineDir}/Plugins/ — engine-bundled plugins, available to all projects
{ProjectDir}/Plugins/ — project-specific plugins

Both directories are scanned at the same time. A project plugin with the same name as an engine plugin will load alongside it (they are not merged or deduplicated).
See Also

Build System — how plugin .build.cs files integrate into ABT and CMake
Hot Reloading — the hot reload mechanism plugins use
Annotations — plugins can register annotations externally during OnLoad

Resonance.content:
Resonance
Resonance is the high-performance, thread-agnostic messaging system in Alchemy Engine. It serves as the “nervous system” of the engine, allowing disparate systems (Physics, UI, Gameplay, AI) to communicate without tight coupling.
Resonance is built on top of the Job System and Tag System, making it both highly concurrent and expressively filterable.
Core Concepts
1. Frequency (Channels)
Messages are broadcast on Frequencies, which are represented by Tags (e.g., Game.Event.Explosion). Listeners subscribe to these frequencies using Tag Queries, allowing for powerful hierarchical matching (e.g., listening to Game.Event receives all child events).
2. Payload
Any struct registered with the TypeRegistry can be sent as a payload. Resonance uses a type-erased container (InstancedStruct) to safely copy and pass this data to listeners across threads.
3. Resonate (Broadcast)
“Resonating” is the act of sending a message. This is a non-blocking operation. The message is packaged into a Job and dispatched to the Job System for asynchronous execution.
4. Endpoints
By default, messages are global. Endpoints allow for private, targeted communication. An object (like a UI Window or Entity Component) can create a ResonanceEndpoint and listeners can bind specifically to it, ignoring global traffic.

Usage Guide
Defining a Payload
Any struct can be a payload. It just needs to be reflected.
struct [[Reflect]] DamagePayload
{
    float Amount;
    EntityHandle Instigator;
    Vector3 Location;
};
Listening to a Frequency
To receive messages, you “Listen” using a TagQuery. You also specify where you want the code to run (Main Thread vs Worker Thread) and its priority.
// 1. Define the filter (Listen to all &#039;Damage&#039; events)
TagQuery DamageFilter = TagQuery::MatchTag(Tags::Game_Damage);

// 2. Subscribe
ResonanceListenerHandle Handle = ResonanceSubsystem::Listen(
    DamageFilter, 
    [](const ResonanceMessage&amp; Msg) 
    {
        // 3. Access Payload
        const auto* Data = Msg.GetPayload&lt;DamagePayload&gt;();
        if(Data)
        {
            Log(&quot;Took {} damage from Entity {}&quot;, Data-&gt;Amount, Data-&gt;Instigator.ID);
        }
    },
    JobAffinity::Worker, // Run this on any background worker thread
    JobPriority::High    // Prioritize this job
);
Stopping a Listener
When you no longer need updates, use the handle to stop listening.
ResonanceSubsystem::StopListening(Handle);
Resonating (Broadcasting)
Sending a message is simple and thread-safe.
// Create payload
DamagePayload Payload;
Payload.Amount = 50.0f;
Payload.Instigator = MyEntity;

// Broadcast globally on &#039;Game.Damage.Physical&#039;
ResonanceSubsystem::Resonate(Game_Damage_Physical, Payload);

Advanced: Endpoints (Targeted Messaging)
Endpoints are useful when you want to communicate with a specific instance of a system rather than the whole world. For example, a specific UI Window updating its content.
1. Creating an Endpoint
The owner of the private channel creates an endpoint.
class InventoryWindow
{
    ResonanceEndpoint MyEndpoint;

    void Init()
    {
        // Listen ONLY to messages sent to &#039;MyEndpoint&#039;
        ResonanceSubsystem::Listen(&amp;MyEndpoint, TagQuery::MatchTag(UI_Update), 
            [this](const ResonanceMessage&amp; Msg) {
                RefreshUI();
            }
        );
    }
};
2. Sending to an Endpoint
The sender must have access to the endpoint object.
void InventoryComponent::OnItemAdded()
{
    // Send specifically to the window&#039;s endpoint
    ResonanceSubsystem::Resonate(&amp;Window-&gt;MyEndpoint, Tags::UI_Update, ItemPayload{...});
}

Debugging
Resonance includes built-in debugging features to help trace message flow.

Source Tracking: Every message automatically captures the filename, function, and line number of the sender (Resonate call site).
Logging: The system logs registration and dispatch counts to the console.

Architecture &amp; Performance

Zero-Copy (Conceptually): The payload is wrapped in a std::shared_ptr when dispatched. If there are 100 listeners, the payload data is NOT copied 100 times; all listeners share read-only access to the same data.
Job System Integration: Resonance listeners are executed as individual Jobs. This allows the engine to automatically load-balance message processing across all available CPU cores.
Tag Query Optimization: Tag matching is highly optimized using the engine’s token-stream query evaluator.

See Also

Tags — tags define the frequencies (channels) messages are broadcast on
Tag Query — used to subscribe to frequency ranges
Jobs — listeners are dispatched as jobs
Instanced Struct — the payload container used by Resonance

Tags/Tag-Query.content:
Tag Query System
The Tag Query system provides a powerful and efficient way to check if a TagContainer or TagCounterContainer matches a specific set of criteria. It supports complex boolean logic (AND, OR, NOT) and hierarchical tag matching.
Overview
Queries are built using a fluent, nested syntax that compiles down to a compact Token Stream for high-performance evaluation.

Fast Execution: Uses a flat byte-code interpreter to avoid recursion and pointer chasing.
Hierarchical: All tag checks respect parent/child relationships (e.g., checking for Weapon matches Weapon.Sword).
Universal: Works on both TagContainer and TagCounterContainer.

Creating a Query
You construct queries using the static builder methods on the TagQuery class.
Basic Matchers
TagQuery::MatchTag(Tag)Matches if the container has the specific tag or any of its children.TagQuery::MatchAllTags({ A, B })Matches if the container has ALL of the specified tags.TagQuery::MatchAnyTags({ A, B })Matches if the container has AT LEAST ONE of the specified tags.TagQuery::MatchNoTags({ A, B })Matches if the container has NONE of the specified tags.
Logic Operators
TagQuery::MatchAll({ Q1, Q2 })AND: Matches only if all sub-queries match.TagQuery::MatchAny({ Q1, Q2 })OR: Matches if at least one sub-query matches.TagQuery::MatchNot(Q)NOT: Inverts the result of the sub-query.
Example
// Check if an entity has (Weapon OR Spell) AND NOT Dead
TagQuery CombatCapableQuery = TagQuery::MatchAll({
    // Condition 1: Must have offensive capability
    TagQuery::MatchAny({
        TagQuery::MatchTag(Tags::Weapon),
        TagQuery::MatchTag(Tags::Spell)
    }),

    // Condition 2: Must NOT be dead
    TagQuery::MatchNot(TagQuery::MatchTag(Tags::State_Dead))
});
Executing a Query
Once built, you can run the query against any container.
TagContainer MyContainer;
// ... fill container ...

if(CombatCapableQuery.Matches(MyContainer))
{
    // Logic for combat capable entities
}
Performance Tips

Reuse Queries: Build your TagQuery objects once (e.g., as static or member variables) and reuse them. Building a query involves memory allocation, but executing it is allocation-free.
Prefer Bulk Matchers: Use MatchAnyTags({A, B}) instead of MatchAny({ MatchTag(A), MatchTag(B) }). The bulk matchers use optimized code paths.

See Also

Tags — the tag definitions and containers that queries operate on
Resonance — uses TagQuery to match message frequencies

Tags/Tags.content:
Tags are a hierarchical tagging system similar to Unreal Engine’s Gameplay Tags system, but we favour speed and power over convenience.
What is a tag?
In reality, a tag is just a number. When the engine is started, all defined tags are registered, sorted into a hierarchical tree and given a number. This number is used to compare tags, fetch parents/children, and simplifies many queries.
A tag being a simple number is what grants us tremendous speeds.

Comparing two tags is just a integer comparison, which means that checking for exact tags is blazing fast.
Performing a child check is just a Child.ID &gt;= Parent.Start &amp;&amp; Child.ID &lt;= Parent.End  check operation.
Performing a parent check is just a Parent.ID &lt;= Child.ID &amp;&amp; Parent.End &gt;= Child.ID check operation.

This means at worst, we are doing 3 to 4 machine instructions per tag.
Tag Container
A tag container is a simple array of tags that ensures only one copy of each tag is present.
Tag Counter Container
Identical to Tag Container, but it keeps a number for each tag. Adding a tag increments its counter by 1 and removing the tag decrements its counter by 1. The tag is only fully removed once the counter reaches 0.
Defining Tags
Alchemy provides 2 macros:

DEFINE_TAG() - This is the simple version

// Define simple tags
DEFINE_TAG(Weapon);
DEFINE_TAG(Weapon_Melee);
DEFINE_TAG(Weapon_Ranged);

DEFINE_TAG() - This allows you to create annotated tags.

// Define annotated tag
DEFINE_TAG_ANNOTATED(Weapon_Melee_Sword, {
    ADD_ANNOTATION(Alchemy::EditorIcon{&quot;Icons/Sword.png&quot;});
});

DEFINE_TAG_ANNOTATED(Status_Stunned, {
    ADD_ANNOTATION(Alchemy::EditorIcon{&quot;Icons/Stun.png&quot;});
});
Tag Component
Entities can have tags applied to them via the TagComponent, then queried through it.
This tag system is not the same as other ECS’s tags. In other ECS’s, like Flecs, a tag is just an empty component. For Alchemy, a tag is much slower, but far more powerful.

The speed: In Alchemy, we can’t narrow down an archetype via tags. Instead, we have to process each entity and perform the tag query. Although, since we have heavily optimized the tag query system, this is still blazing fast.
The power: Since we are using hierarchical tags, we can fetch all entities with complex tag queries. For example; getting all entities who have a tag that’s a child of Entity.Type.Tree. This will return all entities that have tags such as Entity.Type.Tree.Pine and Entity.Type.Tree.Burch.

Tag Entities
//Not yet implemented
Entities can be created and tied to a specific tag on another entities tag. This in essence allows you to add any data you want onto a tag on an entity via components.
This is particularly useful for temporary tags. You can give a tag entity a Lifetime component to have the tag be removed once the tag dies.
See Also

Tag Query — building complex boolean queries over tag containers
Resonance — uses tags as message frequencies
Tags and Markers — how tags and markers interact with the ECS
